WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.916 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.916 --> 00:00:03.832 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:03.832 --> 00:00:05.269 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:05.269 --> 00:00:11.030 align:middle line:90%


00:00:11.030 --> 00:00:12.600 align:middle line:84%
LARRY GUTH: In
just the last year,

00:00:12.600 --> 00:00:17.220 align:middle line:84%
the sharp projection
theorem in R2 was proven.

00:00:17.220 --> 00:00:20.120 align:middle line:90%
And the proof is fairly big.

00:00:20.120 --> 00:00:21.120 align:middle line:90%
It's fairly complicated.

00:00:21.120 --> 00:00:23.840 align:middle line:84%
But for the last
three classes, I'm

00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:25.520 align:middle line:84%
going to want to
circle back to that

00:00:25.520 --> 00:00:29.510 align:middle line:84%
and talk about the new
ideas in that proof.

00:00:29.510 --> 00:00:32.390 align:middle line:84%
So it's been a while since
we talked about it, so I

00:00:32.390 --> 00:00:34.250 align:middle line:90%
thought we could start by--

00:00:34.250 --> 00:00:38.794 align:middle line:84%
we'll start just by writing
down what is the statement.

00:00:38.794 --> 00:00:42.200 align:middle line:84%
So this projection theory,
I like to think of it

00:00:42.200 --> 00:00:47.780 align:middle line:84%
as a geometric measure theory
analog of the Szemerédi--Trotter

00:00:47.780 --> 00:00:48.450 align:middle line:90%
theorem.

00:00:48.450 --> 00:00:50.540 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to start by writing
down the Szemerédi--Trotter

00:00:50.540 --> 00:00:51.040 align:middle line:90%
theorem.

00:00:51.040 --> 00:00:53.990 align:middle line:90%


00:00:53.990 --> 00:00:58.670 align:middle line:90%
So sharp projection.

00:00:58.670 --> 00:01:03.030 align:middle line:90%


00:01:03.030 --> 00:01:08.400 align:middle line:84%
Start by writing down the
Szemerédi--Trotter theorem.

00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:10.570 align:middle line:84%
And there are a bunch
of different versions.

00:01:10.570 --> 00:01:12.810 align:middle line:84%
And I've picked out a
particular version that

00:01:12.810 --> 00:01:15.060 align:middle line:84%
fits into the way
the proof is going

00:01:15.060 --> 00:01:17.850 align:middle line:84%
to go for this sharp
projection theorem.

00:01:17.850 --> 00:01:20.350 align:middle line:90%
So it says the following thing.

00:01:20.350 --> 00:01:26.070 align:middle line:84%
So if E is a finite
subset of R2,

00:01:26.070 --> 00:01:33.930 align:middle line:84%
and then L is a set of
lines, let's say it this way.

00:01:33.930 --> 00:01:42.930 align:middle line:84%
For every x in E, we'll
have LxE is a set of S lines

00:01:42.930 --> 00:01:45.690 align:middle line:90%
that go through x.

00:01:45.690 --> 00:01:51.730 align:middle line:84%
And L is the union
over x at LxE.

00:01:51.730 --> 00:01:56.892 align:middle line:90%


00:01:56.892 --> 00:01:59.560 align:middle line:84%
So this set of lines L,
there's at least S of them

00:01:59.560 --> 00:02:05.195 align:middle line:90%
through every point of E.

00:02:05.195 --> 00:02:09.639 align:middle line:84%
So then, conclusion is
that the number of lines

00:02:09.639 --> 00:02:13.280 align:middle line:84%
is at least the minimum
of a couple of options.

00:02:13.280 --> 00:02:18.520 align:middle line:84%
There's the size of E times
S, or there's the size of E

00:02:18.520 --> 00:02:22.060 align:middle line:90%
to the 1/2 S to the 3/2.

00:02:22.060 --> 00:02:29.350 align:middle line:84%
We'll call this
option A and option B.

00:02:29.350 --> 00:02:32.900 align:middle line:84%
Option A, it's very simple to
imagine how this could arise.

00:02:32.900 --> 00:02:37.450 align:middle line:84%
I have a bunch of points,
set E. And for each point,

00:02:37.450 --> 00:02:40.240 align:middle line:90%
I have S lines through it.

00:02:40.240 --> 00:02:42.320 align:middle line:84%
And they're just all
different from each other,

00:02:42.320 --> 00:02:46.070 align:middle line:90%
so I get E times S lines.

00:02:46.070 --> 00:02:51.200 align:middle line:84%
Option B is more
special, more remarkable,

00:02:51.200 --> 00:02:53.000 align:middle line:90%
although not that complicated.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:54.830 align:middle line:90%
It's an integer grid.

00:02:54.830 --> 00:02:56.490 align:middle line:84%
And we talked about
it a couple times

00:02:56.490 --> 00:02:57.740 align:middle line:90%
in the beginning of the class.

00:02:57.740 --> 00:03:01.510 align:middle line:90%


00:03:01.510 --> 00:03:07.035 align:middle line:84%
So an integer grid, that
would make some sense.

00:03:07.035 --> 00:03:10.885 align:middle line:90%


00:03:10.885 --> 00:03:13.010 align:middle line:84%
So we might have a lot of
lines through each point.

00:03:13.010 --> 00:03:15.560 align:middle line:84%
But still, each line is
going through many points.

00:03:15.560 --> 00:03:19.430 align:middle line:84%
So the total number of lines
is a lot less than E times S.

00:03:19.430 --> 00:03:21.060 align:middle line:84%
And if you work it
out, you get this.

00:03:21.060 --> 00:03:24.040 align:middle line:90%


00:03:24.040 --> 00:03:26.890 align:middle line:84%
So that's the
Szemerédi--Trotter theorem.

00:03:26.890 --> 00:03:30.100 align:middle line:84%
We saw early on that it
implies a sharp projection

00:03:30.100 --> 00:03:33.130 align:middle line:90%
theorem for finite sets in R2.

00:03:33.130 --> 00:03:36.460 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to try to do
some analog for delta balls

00:03:36.460 --> 00:03:39.140 align:middle line:90%
in R2.

00:03:39.140 --> 00:03:42.195 align:middle line:84%
When we talk about delta balls,
it matters how they're spaced.

00:03:42.195 --> 00:03:44.320 align:middle line:84%
And the spacing condition
we're going to talk about

00:03:44.320 --> 00:03:45.850 align:middle line:84%
is the one that
Pablo introduced,

00:03:45.850 --> 00:03:48.100 align:middle line:90%
the delta SC condition.

00:03:48.100 --> 00:03:50.140 align:middle line:90%
So I'll make a definition.

00:03:50.140 --> 00:03:55.860 align:middle line:84%
So if E is a subset
of R to the D,

00:03:55.860 --> 00:04:03.230 align:middle line:84%
we're going to say that
E is delta S, C if--

00:04:03.230 --> 00:04:05.480 align:middle line:84%
so first of all, I'm
going to imagine here

00:04:05.480 --> 00:04:13.580 align:middle line:84%
that E is contained in a unit
ball or almost unit ball.

00:04:13.580 --> 00:04:18.140 align:middle line:84%
And then, if you take
E, and you intersect it

00:04:18.140 --> 00:04:25.350 align:middle line:84%
with a smaller ball, it's
basically a new ball.

00:04:25.350 --> 00:04:27.740 align:middle line:84%
If you take E, and you
intersect it with a smaller ball

00:04:27.740 --> 00:04:30.000 align:middle line:84%
and take the delta-covering
number of that,

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:33.200 align:middle line:84%
then that should be smaller
than C times little r

00:04:33.200 --> 00:04:35.540 align:middle line:84%
to the S times the
delta-covering number

00:04:35.540 --> 00:04:38.480 align:middle line:90%
of the whole set.

00:04:38.480 --> 00:04:44.420 align:middle line:84%
So for any x and for any r
which should be at least delta.

00:04:44.420 --> 00:04:46.950 align:middle line:90%
So that's a delta S, C set.

00:04:46.950 --> 00:04:49.160 align:middle line:84%
It's a spacing
condition on the set E

00:04:49.160 --> 00:04:51.990 align:middle line:84%
that says that it's
not too concentrated

00:04:51.990 --> 00:04:53.465 align:middle line:90%
into any smaller ball.

00:04:53.465 --> 00:05:02.496 align:middle line:90%


00:05:02.496 --> 00:05:06.300 align:middle line:84%
So here is the statement of
the sharp projection theorem.

00:05:06.300 --> 00:05:14.740 align:middle line:84%
So the theorem of Orponen and
Shmerkin, Ren, Wang from 2024.

00:05:14.740 --> 00:05:29.340 align:middle line:84%
So if E in R2 is a delta
S, C set, then every x in E

00:05:29.340 --> 00:05:33.720 align:middle line:84%
will have a set
of tubes T sub x.

00:05:33.720 --> 00:05:41.270 align:middle line:84%
This is a set of
delta tubes through x.

00:05:41.270 --> 00:05:44.190 align:middle line:90%


00:05:44.190 --> 00:05:47.650 align:middle line:84%
And sorry, E is going to be--
this is just a notation choice,

00:05:47.650 --> 00:05:49.730 align:middle line:84%
but if I don't match my
notes, I'll go bananas.

00:05:49.730 --> 00:05:52.840 align:middle line:90%
It's a delta t, C set.

00:05:52.840 --> 00:05:56.000 align:middle line:84%
And so for each point, there's
a set of tubes through it.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:07.130 align:middle line:84%
And this set of tubes is
a delta S, C set in S1.

00:06:07.130 --> 00:06:08.900 align:middle line:90%
So let's make a picture.

00:06:08.900 --> 00:06:13.390 align:middle line:84%
So we have the set E,
which you may as well think

00:06:13.390 --> 00:06:15.730 align:middle line:90%
of as a set of delta balls.

00:06:15.730 --> 00:06:18.820 align:middle line:84%
So there's E. And then for
each of these delta balls,

00:06:18.820 --> 00:06:20.325 align:middle line:90%
it lies in a bunch of tubes.

00:06:20.325 --> 00:06:29.500 align:middle line:90%


00:06:29.500 --> 00:06:32.025 align:middle line:84%
And we'll repeat for
all of these other guys.

00:06:32.025 --> 00:06:34.150 align:middle line:84%
Maybe this tube keeps going
and goes through there,

00:06:34.150 --> 00:06:35.690 align:middle line:90%
and this tube there.

00:06:35.690 --> 00:06:40.690 align:middle line:84%
So if this is x, those
tubes there, that's Tx.

00:06:40.690 --> 00:06:43.280 align:middle line:84%
And they point in
different directions.

00:06:43.280 --> 00:06:47.170 align:middle line:84%
You can think of the directions
as being parametrized by S1.

00:06:47.170 --> 00:06:50.720 align:middle line:84%
And they are a delta
S, C set in S1.

00:06:50.720 --> 00:06:51.310 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:06:51.310 --> 00:06:53.230 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: What if you
use multiple tubes that

00:06:53.230 --> 00:06:54.820 align:middle line:84%
are in the same
direction, slightly

00:06:54.820 --> 00:06:56.560 align:middle line:90%
offset of each other that--

00:06:56.560 --> 00:07:00.310 align:middle line:90%
I guess, less delta [INAUDIBLE]

00:07:00.310 --> 00:07:04.300 align:middle line:84%
LARRY GUTH: Yeah, so if you--
right, so if I had this point,

00:07:04.300 --> 00:07:07.550 align:middle line:90%
and then I had those--

00:07:07.550 --> 00:07:09.760 align:middle line:90%
oh, I see.

00:07:09.760 --> 00:07:11.850 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, we'll think of
those as the same tube.

00:07:11.850 --> 00:07:15.730 align:middle line:90%


00:07:15.730 --> 00:07:16.230 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:07:16.230 --> 00:07:18.910 align:middle line:90%


00:07:18.910 --> 00:07:21.740 align:middle line:84%
So the question was, if
I have my delta ball,

00:07:21.740 --> 00:07:23.650 align:middle line:84%
could I have two
delta tubes going

00:07:23.650 --> 00:07:26.350 align:middle line:84%
through it that are going
in the same direction

00:07:26.350 --> 00:07:29.080 align:middle line:84%
or within an angle
delta of each other?

00:07:29.080 --> 00:07:31.650 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to think of those as
being basically the same tube.

00:07:31.650 --> 00:07:36.250 align:middle line:90%


00:07:36.250 --> 00:07:43.930 align:middle line:84%
Then T is the union over x of
Tx which could be smaller than

00:07:43.930 --> 00:07:47.210 align:middle line:84%
the sum of them because one tube
might be in Tx for two different

00:07:47.210 --> 00:07:49.040 align:middle line:90%
x's.

00:07:49.040 --> 00:07:51.960 align:middle line:84%
And the question is,
in terms of S and T,

00:07:51.960 --> 00:07:53.680 align:middle line:90%
how big does this need to be?

00:07:53.680 --> 00:07:59.750 align:middle line:90%


00:07:59.750 --> 00:08:06.450 align:middle line:84%
So then the conclusion is that
the size of T is bigger than--

00:08:06.450 --> 00:08:08.700 align:middle line:84%
OK, there's a little
complicated stuff--

00:08:08.700 --> 00:08:15.650 align:middle line:84%
C epsilon delta to the epsilon
big C to the minus order of 1.

00:08:15.650 --> 00:08:20.310 align:middle line:84%
And then there's
the minimum of k.

00:08:20.310 --> 00:08:25.070 align:middle line:84%
So the E times S corresponds
to delta to the minus T delta

00:08:25.070 --> 00:08:27.320 align:middle line:90%
to the minus S.

00:08:27.320 --> 00:08:30.110 align:middle line:84%
So this corresponds to
A. There's somebody that

00:08:30.110 --> 00:08:34.220 align:middle line:84%
corresponds to B, delta to
the minus T over 2 delta

00:08:34.220 --> 00:08:36.299 align:middle line:90%
to the minus 3T over 2.

00:08:36.299 --> 00:08:40.429 align:middle line:84%
That corresponds to B. And
there is a new thing, delta

00:08:40.429 --> 00:08:44.973 align:middle line:84%
to the minus 1 minus S, that
corresponds to C. Sorry,

00:08:44.973 --> 00:08:46.390 align:middle line:84%
it doesn't correspond
to anything.

00:08:46.390 --> 00:08:51.185 align:middle line:84%
There was no C up there, I
will call it C. So who is C?

00:08:51.185 --> 00:09:00.210 align:middle line:90%


00:09:00.210 --> 00:09:03.750 align:middle line:84%
So C is a new phenomenon
that has to do with the fact

00:09:03.750 --> 00:09:06.150 align:middle line:84%
that these tubes and balls
have a thickness, which

00:09:06.150 --> 00:09:07.740 align:middle line:90%
we didn't have up there.

00:09:07.740 --> 00:09:12.515 align:middle line:84%
So here, E could
just be any set.

00:09:12.515 --> 00:09:18.570 align:middle line:90%


00:09:18.570 --> 00:09:26.310 align:middle line:84%
And then T is a random set of
delta to the minus 1 minus S

00:09:26.310 --> 00:09:29.250 align:middle line:90%
or so tubes.

00:09:29.250 --> 00:09:33.480 align:middle line:84%
And the probability that a delta
tube goes through a given point

00:09:33.480 --> 00:09:34.720 align:middle line:90%
is delta.

00:09:34.720 --> 00:09:39.990 align:middle line:84%
So a typical point
Tx would essentially

00:09:39.990 --> 00:09:47.320 align:middle line:84%
be a random set of around
delta to the minus S tubes.

00:09:47.320 --> 00:09:48.797 align:middle line:84%
And a random set--
there might be

00:09:48.797 --> 00:09:51.130 align:middle line:84%
a couple that are close
together, but on the whole, that

00:09:51.130 --> 00:09:55.360 align:middle line:90%
would be a delta S set of tubes.

00:09:55.360 --> 00:09:58.370 align:middle line:84%
OK, so that's where this
new option comes from.

00:09:58.370 --> 00:09:58.870 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:09:58.870 --> 00:10:00.082 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Professor?

00:10:00.082 --> 00:10:00.790 align:middle line:90%
LARRY GUTH: Yeah?

00:10:00.790 --> 00:10:03.610 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: In option B, is
one of the exponents supposed

00:10:03.610 --> 00:10:04.960 align:middle line:90%
to be an S instead of t?

00:10:04.960 --> 00:10:07.810 align:middle line:90%
LARRY GUTH: Yes, thank you.

00:10:07.810 --> 00:10:12.200 align:middle line:84%
That's supposed to
be an S. Correct.

00:10:12.200 --> 00:10:16.180 align:middle line:84%
So let's put these on top
of each other for a second.

00:10:16.180 --> 00:10:20.780 align:middle line:84%
So the size of E corresponds
to the delta to the minus T,

00:10:20.780 --> 00:10:24.670 align:middle line:84%
and big S corresponds to
delta to the minus little S.

00:10:24.670 --> 00:10:27.970 align:middle line:90%
And so those match up.

00:10:27.970 --> 00:10:29.430 align:middle line:90%
And then C is something new.

00:10:29.430 --> 00:10:33.460 align:middle line:90%


00:10:33.460 --> 00:10:34.970 align:middle line:90%
OK, good.

00:10:34.970 --> 00:10:37.450 align:middle line:84%
Now, I realized I
forgot one hypothesis

00:10:37.450 --> 00:10:38.390 align:middle line:90%
that I'm going to add.

00:10:38.390 --> 00:10:41.890 align:middle line:84%
And then we'll pause, and you
can look at these statements.

00:10:41.890 --> 00:10:48.580 align:middle line:84%
So we needed one more
hypothesis in our list

00:10:48.580 --> 00:10:53.380 align:middle line:84%
of hypotheses, which is that
this S should be bigger than 1.

00:10:53.380 --> 00:10:55.960 align:middle line:84%
You see, if I just had one
line going through each

00:10:55.960 --> 00:10:57.490 align:middle line:84%
of these points,
then I could just

00:10:57.490 --> 00:11:00.080 align:middle line:84%
have one line and a
bunch of points on it.

00:11:00.080 --> 00:11:03.120 align:middle line:90%
And 1 is not bigger than this.

00:11:03.120 --> 00:11:05.690 align:middle line:90%


00:11:05.690 --> 00:11:06.980 align:middle line:90%
So that's a special case.

00:11:06.980 --> 00:11:10.360 align:middle line:84%
And there is an
analogous condition here.

00:11:10.360 --> 00:11:12.730 align:middle line:84%
In our list of
hypotheses, we need

00:11:12.730 --> 00:11:15.650 align:middle line:90%
little S to be bigger than 0.

00:11:15.650 --> 00:11:17.855 align:middle line:84%
This corresponds to
having not just one

00:11:17.855 --> 00:11:19.980 align:middle line:84%
tube through each of these
points, but pretty many.

00:11:19.980 --> 00:11:23.710 align:middle line:90%


00:11:23.710 --> 00:11:27.080 align:middle line:84%
So that's the statement
of Szemerédi--Trotter

00:11:27.080 --> 00:11:30.550 align:middle line:84%
and the parallel statement of
this is the Furstenberg set

00:11:30.550 --> 00:11:34.750 align:middle line:90%
conjecture proven just recently.

00:11:34.750 --> 00:11:39.200 align:middle line:84%
So let's pause there
to digest and see

00:11:39.200 --> 00:11:41.450 align:middle line:84%
if there are questions or
comments about the statement

00:11:41.450 --> 00:11:42.130 align:middle line:90%
of this theorem.

00:11:42.130 --> 00:11:53.390 align:middle line:90%


00:11:53.390 --> 00:11:54.262 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:11:54.262 --> 00:11:56.720 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: I'm still having a
hard time understanding what's

00:11:56.720 --> 00:12:01.430 align:middle line:84%
going on in case C. Would
it be possible to draw

00:12:01.430 --> 00:12:02.762 align:middle line:90%
a typical example?

00:12:02.762 --> 00:12:03.470 align:middle line:90%
LARRY GUTH: Yeah.

00:12:03.470 --> 00:12:09.090 align:middle line:84%
Let's draw case C So
E could go anywhere.

00:12:09.090 --> 00:12:14.630 align:middle line:90%


00:12:14.630 --> 00:12:22.460 align:middle line:84%
And then I am going to
draw a random set of tubes,

00:12:22.460 --> 00:12:25.730 align:middle line:90%
a bunch of them.

00:12:25.730 --> 00:12:27.055 align:middle line:90%
So here I go.

00:12:27.055 --> 00:12:32.570 align:middle line:90%


00:12:32.570 --> 00:12:37.110 align:middle line:84%
So I drew these tubes,
or I tried to do it,

00:12:37.110 --> 00:12:39.520 align:middle line:84%
without thinking at all
about where the points are.

00:12:39.520 --> 00:12:43.350 align:middle line:84%
There was nothing
clever going on.

00:12:43.350 --> 00:12:46.930 align:middle line:90%
But I drew a whole lot of them.

00:12:46.930 --> 00:12:53.230 align:middle line:84%
And 1 over-- a delta fraction,
if I draw a random tube,

00:12:53.230 --> 00:12:55.500 align:middle line:84%
the probability that it
goes through here is delta.

00:12:55.500 --> 00:13:00.370 align:middle line:84%
So if I draw M times 1
over delta random tubes,

00:13:00.370 --> 00:13:03.600 align:middle line:84%
I'll have about M of them
going through this point.

00:13:03.600 --> 00:13:04.780 align:middle line:90%
So let's say I do that.

00:13:04.780 --> 00:13:06.970 align:middle line:84%
So I have about M tubes
going through this point.

00:13:06.970 --> 00:13:09.100 align:middle line:84%
Now, what directions
will they point in?

00:13:09.100 --> 00:13:11.070 align:middle line:84%
Well, they'll point
in random directions.

00:13:11.070 --> 00:13:16.930 align:middle line:84%
And a random direction-- a
random set is a delta S, C set,

00:13:16.930 --> 00:13:20.760 align:middle line:84%
where's where delta to the
minus S is the number of points.

00:13:20.760 --> 00:13:24.395 align:middle line:90%
So that's why we have this.

00:13:24.395 --> 00:13:26.910 align:middle line:90%


00:13:26.910 --> 00:13:28.610 align:middle line:90%
OK, other questions or comments?

00:13:28.610 --> 00:13:35.095 align:middle line:90%


00:13:35.095 --> 00:13:38.560 align:middle line:84%
So now let's start talking
about the history of work

00:13:38.560 --> 00:13:39.330 align:middle line:90%
on this problem.

00:13:39.330 --> 00:13:42.310 align:middle line:90%


00:13:42.310 --> 00:13:45.640 align:middle line:84%
And going through the history
of work on the problem

00:13:45.640 --> 00:13:49.100 align:middle line:84%
will also be an excuse
to recap a big section,

00:13:49.100 --> 00:13:52.270 align:middle line:90%
big chunks of our class.

00:13:52.270 --> 00:14:04.330 align:middle line:84%
So history of work slash
recap of the class.

00:14:04.330 --> 00:14:05.360 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:14:05.360 --> 00:14:10.390 align:middle line:84%
So first, I'll do what I'll
call classical bounds, which

00:14:10.390 --> 00:14:14.313 align:middle line:84%
are essentially due to
Kaufman and Falconer.

00:14:14.313 --> 00:14:19.630 align:middle line:90%


00:14:19.630 --> 00:14:23.523 align:middle line:84%
And they were written up in
the context of this theorem.

00:14:23.523 --> 00:14:25.940 align:middle line:84%
Kaufman and Falconer were
talking about projection theory.

00:14:25.940 --> 00:14:29.230 align:middle line:84%
This is a little
bit more general.

00:14:29.230 --> 00:14:31.030 align:middle line:90%
But they were written up.

00:14:31.030 --> 00:14:35.110 align:middle line:84%
Kaufman and Falconer were in the
'60s and '70s, so a pretty long

00:14:35.110 --> 00:14:40.750 align:middle line:84%
time ago, and then
adapted a bit by Wolff.

00:14:40.750 --> 00:14:45.180 align:middle line:84%
The first classical
argument is double counter.

00:14:45.180 --> 00:14:48.733 align:middle line:90%


00:14:48.733 --> 00:14:50.650 align:middle line:84%
There are actually two
slightly different ways

00:14:50.650 --> 00:14:52.450 align:middle line:90%
of doing double counting.

00:14:52.450 --> 00:14:54.220 align:middle line:90%
I'll tell you what they give.

00:14:54.220 --> 00:14:59.650 align:middle line:84%
The first way gives
that, if S is at least T,

00:14:59.650 --> 00:15:06.616 align:middle line:84%
then the number of tubes
is at least option A.

00:15:06.616 --> 00:15:10.180 align:middle line:90%
And this is sharp.

00:15:10.180 --> 00:15:13.630 align:middle line:84%
So let's think
about what it means.

00:15:13.630 --> 00:15:17.980 align:middle line:84%
So S is at least T. That means
that the number of directions

00:15:17.980 --> 00:15:23.710 align:middle line:84%
through each point is bigger
than the number of points.

00:15:23.710 --> 00:15:29.570 align:middle line:84%
So let me draw a little
picture to the side here.

00:15:29.570 --> 00:15:32.610 align:middle line:84%
So I have a few
points, not very many.

00:15:32.610 --> 00:15:34.645 align:middle line:84%
And then through
each tube, I'm going

00:15:34.645 --> 00:15:36.020 align:middle line:84%
to draw-- through
each point, I'm

00:15:36.020 --> 00:15:37.530 align:middle line:90%
going to draw a bunch of tubes.

00:15:37.530 --> 00:15:40.190 align:middle line:84%
And the number of
directions is bigger

00:15:40.190 --> 00:15:42.140 align:middle line:90%
than the number of points.

00:15:42.140 --> 00:15:43.790 align:middle line:90%
So I have a picture like this.

00:15:43.790 --> 00:15:46.520 align:middle line:84%
So what you see is that
most of these tubes

00:15:46.520 --> 00:15:51.530 align:middle line:84%
don't go through any other
point besides the initial point.

00:15:51.530 --> 00:15:56.330 align:middle line:84%
And that gives an easy estimate
for the number of tubes,

00:15:56.330 --> 00:15:59.850 align:middle line:84%
has to be at least the number of
points times the number of tubes

00:15:59.850 --> 00:16:00.600 align:middle line:90%
through the point.

00:16:00.600 --> 00:16:03.890 align:middle line:90%


00:16:03.890 --> 00:16:06.710 align:middle line:84%
There is another way
to do double counting.

00:16:06.710 --> 00:16:12.420 align:middle line:84%
And it says that, in general,
so just if S is bigger than 0,

00:16:12.420 --> 00:16:16.820 align:middle line:84%
which we've been assuming, then
the number of tubes is at least

00:16:16.820 --> 00:16:18.453 align:middle line:90%
delta to the minus 2S.

00:16:18.453 --> 00:16:36.150 align:middle line:90%


00:16:36.150 --> 00:16:39.370 align:middle line:84%
So let me just leave
this one as an exercise.

00:16:39.370 --> 00:16:41.225 align:middle line:90%
We've done some double counting.

00:16:41.225 --> 00:16:45.210 align:middle line:90%


00:16:45.210 --> 00:16:57.160 align:middle line:84%
Then there was a Fourier
method that we did in class.

00:16:57.160 --> 00:17:01.440 align:middle line:84%
And the Fourier method
showed that T was bigger

00:17:01.440 --> 00:17:04.660 align:middle line:90%
than the minimum of two things.

00:17:04.660 --> 00:17:08.040 align:middle line:84%
One of them is option
C, And the other one

00:17:08.040 --> 00:17:14.339 align:middle line:84%
is delta to the 1
minus S times option A.

00:17:14.339 --> 00:17:17.619 align:middle line:84%
And so this number
is smaller than 1.

00:17:17.619 --> 00:17:19.740 align:middle line:90%
So this is smaller than A.

00:17:19.740 --> 00:17:23.220 align:middle line:84%
So this isn't
sharp, unless we're

00:17:23.220 --> 00:17:25.900 align:middle line:84%
so lucky that S is equal to
1, in which case, this is

00:17:25.900 --> 00:17:28.940 align:middle line:84%
the minimum of A and
C, and that's good.

00:17:28.940 --> 00:17:34.310 align:middle line:84%
So this is sharp
if S is equal to 1.

00:17:34.310 --> 00:17:37.285 align:middle line:90%


00:17:37.285 --> 00:17:40.690 align:middle line:84%
So I won't redo this one, but
this is just the Fourier method

00:17:40.690 --> 00:17:43.840 align:middle line:84%
that we did in the
third week of our class.

00:17:43.840 --> 00:17:46.520 align:middle line:90%


00:17:46.520 --> 00:17:49.300 align:middle line:84%
So the classical methods
are occasionally sharp,

00:17:49.300 --> 00:17:50.565 align:middle line:90%
but usually not.

00:17:50.565 --> 00:18:08.260 align:middle line:90%


00:18:08.260 --> 00:18:11.200 align:middle line:84%
So another comment
about this story,

00:18:11.200 --> 00:18:15.880 align:middle line:84%
about why this is difficult, is
that some of these statements

00:18:15.880 --> 00:18:17.330 align:middle line:90%
are field-dependent.

00:18:17.330 --> 00:18:19.850 align:middle line:84%
They're true over R, but
they're false over C.

00:18:19.850 --> 00:18:24.280 align:middle line:84%
But others are
true in all fields.

00:18:24.280 --> 00:18:28.750 align:middle line:84%
So if we go back
to the beginning,

00:18:28.750 --> 00:18:33.318 align:middle line:84%
the Szemerédi--Trotter theorem
is true in both R and C,

00:18:33.318 --> 00:18:34.860 align:middle line:84%
although it's not
true in all fields.

00:18:34.860 --> 00:18:39.670 align:middle line:90%


00:18:39.670 --> 00:18:45.017 align:middle line:84%
It is the false in
some finite fields.

00:18:45.017 --> 00:18:47.100 align:middle line:84%
Well, as written, it's
false in all finite fields.

00:18:47.100 --> 00:18:53.410 align:middle line:90%


00:18:53.410 --> 00:19:02.650 align:middle line:84%
This theorem here is true over
R, but it is false over C.

00:19:02.650 --> 00:19:05.860 align:middle line:84%
And that counterexample has
kind of haunted all of us

00:19:05.860 --> 00:19:08.440 align:middle line:90%
who have been working on this.

00:19:08.440 --> 00:19:10.870 align:middle line:84%
And one feature of
these classical methods

00:19:10.870 --> 00:19:13.810 align:middle line:90%
is that they don't distinguish.

00:19:13.810 --> 00:19:24.085 align:middle line:90%
They work over R or C.

00:19:24.085 --> 00:19:26.460 align:middle line:84%
So to prove this theorem, we
have to distinguish R and C.

00:19:26.460 --> 00:19:28.502 align:middle line:84%
So we'll have to do
something which, in some way,

00:19:28.502 --> 00:19:30.200 align:middle line:90%
is different from these.

00:19:30.200 --> 00:19:33.130 align:middle line:84%
And the next phase
in the history

00:19:33.130 --> 00:19:35.790 align:middle line:84%
begins with Bourgain's
projection theorem.

00:19:35.790 --> 00:19:39.176 align:middle line:84%
And it's a phase that I'll
label as epsilon improvements.

00:19:39.176 --> 00:19:48.497 align:middle line:90%


00:19:48.497 --> 00:19:50.330 align:middle line:84%
So for quite a while,
actually, there really

00:19:50.330 --> 00:19:52.920 align:middle line:84%
was no progress on
these classical methods.

00:19:52.920 --> 00:19:55.610 align:middle line:84%
These classical methods
are from the '60s and '70s.

00:19:55.610 --> 00:19:58.050 align:middle line:84%
Wolff adapted them to
slightly more general setting,

00:19:58.050 --> 00:20:01.730 align:middle line:84%
but basically, there was no
progress for a long time.

00:20:01.730 --> 00:20:08.570 align:middle line:84%
And phase II is the phase
of epsilon improvements.

00:20:08.570 --> 00:20:11.750 align:middle line:84%
And the dates of this
phase are from around 2000

00:20:11.750 --> 00:20:23.400 align:middle line:84%
to very recently, whereas the
Bourgain projections theorem,

00:20:23.400 --> 00:20:27.030 align:middle line:84%
it implies, with a little
work but not that much work,

00:20:27.030 --> 00:20:30.270 align:middle line:84%
an improvement over
the classical methods

00:20:30.270 --> 00:20:33.060 align:middle line:90%
in a very particular situation.

00:20:33.060 --> 00:20:39.390 align:middle line:84%
So it says, if T
is 1, and S is 1/2,

00:20:39.390 --> 00:20:47.010 align:middle line:84%
then this number of tubes is at
least delta to the minus 1 minus

00:20:47.010 --> 00:20:50.010 align:middle line:90%
some epsilon for that.

00:20:50.010 --> 00:20:52.810 align:middle line:84%
So if you just plug in the
classical bounds up there,

00:20:52.810 --> 00:20:53.880 align:middle line:90%
it would give this.

00:20:53.880 --> 00:20:57.180 align:middle line:84%
And there's an
improvement, although only

00:20:57.180 --> 00:20:58.980 align:middle line:84%
for a rather
particular-- for one

00:20:58.980 --> 00:21:01.226 align:middle line:84%
particular choice
of the parameters.

00:21:01.226 --> 00:21:06.140 align:middle line:90%


00:21:06.140 --> 00:21:09.660 align:middle line:90%
So that was in 2000.

00:21:09.660 --> 00:21:14.610 align:middle line:84%
And the next improvement is a
theorem of Orponen and Shmerkin

00:21:14.610 --> 00:21:17.950 align:middle line:90%
from 2021.

00:21:17.950 --> 00:21:20.750 align:middle line:84%
And you can think of it as
a generalization of this.

00:21:20.750 --> 00:21:22.630 align:middle line:84%
It gives an epsilon
improvement, but in

00:21:22.630 --> 00:21:25.280 align:middle line:84%
not just for this special
value of the parameters,

00:21:25.280 --> 00:21:27.490 align:middle line:84%
but for lots of values
of the parameters.

00:21:27.490 --> 00:21:33.340 align:middle line:84%
So they proved that,
if T is bigger than S,

00:21:33.340 --> 00:21:41.110 align:middle line:84%
which is bigger than 0, then
the number of tubes is at least

00:21:41.110 --> 00:21:45.730 align:middle line:84%
delta to the minus
2S minus epsilon.

00:21:45.730 --> 00:21:48.940 align:middle line:84%
So delta to the minus 2S is
what you would get classically

00:21:48.940 --> 00:21:50.380 align:middle line:90%
by double counting.

00:21:50.380 --> 00:21:52.870 align:middle line:90%
It takes half a page.

00:21:52.870 --> 00:21:58.305 align:middle line:84%
And then, after 50 years and
50 pages, you can get this.

00:21:58.305 --> 00:22:04.060 align:middle line:90%


00:22:04.060 --> 00:22:10.390 align:middle line:84%
So in our class, we said a lot
about the proof of the Bourgain

00:22:10.390 --> 00:22:11.660 align:middle line:90%
projection theorem.

00:22:11.660 --> 00:22:14.170 align:middle line:84%
I actually wouldn't
say that we proved--

00:22:14.170 --> 00:22:15.850 align:middle line:90%
did every step, every detail.

00:22:15.850 --> 00:22:19.985 align:middle line:90%


00:22:19.985 --> 00:22:21.610 align:middle line:84%
We haven't proven
this, but let me just

00:22:21.610 --> 00:22:22.940 align:middle line:90%
say something about the proof.

00:22:22.940 --> 00:22:26.080 align:middle line:84%
So this is based on
Bourgain projection

00:22:26.080 --> 00:22:30.975 align:middle line:90%
theorem, plus a bunch of ideas.

00:22:30.975 --> 00:22:34.980 align:middle line:90%


00:22:34.980 --> 00:22:36.970 align:middle line:84%
And so an emotional
reaction that I

00:22:36.970 --> 00:22:40.120 align:middle line:84%
had to learning this and
going through it with you

00:22:40.120 --> 00:22:44.650 align:middle line:90%
is that it is hard work.

00:22:44.650 --> 00:22:48.250 align:middle line:84%
And also, epsilon
is really tiny.

00:22:48.250 --> 00:22:51.320 align:middle line:84%
It seems like the cleverer
we are, the harder we work,

00:22:51.320 --> 00:22:52.683 align:middle line:90%
we keep making epsilon smaller.

00:22:52.683 --> 00:22:57.560 align:middle line:90%


00:22:57.560 --> 00:22:59.740 align:middle line:84%
So this was the second
phase of the history,

00:22:59.740 --> 00:23:02.630 align:middle line:84%
where people were able to
make epsilon improvements.

00:23:02.630 --> 00:23:04.930 align:middle line:84%
I could also mention
other theorems

00:23:04.930 --> 00:23:08.510 align:middle line:84%
not about this exact problem,
but in a similar spirit.

00:23:08.510 --> 00:23:10.660 align:middle line:84%
So for many different
problems, it

00:23:10.660 --> 00:23:14.150 align:middle line:84%
was possible to make
an epsilon improvement

00:23:14.150 --> 00:23:16.220 align:middle line:84%
by using Bourgain's
projection theorem

00:23:16.220 --> 00:23:18.380 align:middle line:84%
and by using developing
ideas related

00:23:18.380 --> 00:23:21.300 align:middle line:90%
to the ones we put there.

00:23:21.300 --> 00:23:22.220 align:middle line:90%
So it's hard work.

00:23:22.220 --> 00:23:23.580 align:middle line:90%
Epsilon was really tiny.

00:23:23.580 --> 00:23:25.520 align:middle line:84%
But one positive
thing about it is

00:23:25.520 --> 00:23:29.630 align:middle line:84%
that it did distinguish R from
C. So both of these theorems

00:23:29.630 --> 00:23:33.780 align:middle line:84%
are false over C. So we
did start to do that.

00:23:33.780 --> 00:23:38.000 align:middle line:90%


00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:38.790 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:23:38.790 --> 00:23:41.840 align:middle line:84%
So this theorem
represents a third stage

00:23:41.840 --> 00:23:43.820 align:middle line:84%
in the history,
where we didn't just

00:23:43.820 --> 00:23:46.770 align:middle line:84%
improve by an epsilon over
the classical results,

00:23:46.770 --> 00:23:49.290 align:middle line:90%
but we improved substantially.

00:23:49.290 --> 00:23:53.300 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, people
proved the sharp result.

00:23:53.300 --> 00:23:55.450 align:middle line:84%
So sorry, I should
mention, this is sharp.

00:23:55.450 --> 00:23:59.000 align:middle line:90%


00:23:59.000 --> 00:24:05.330 align:middle line:84%
This is sharp for
any S and T. Yeah?

00:24:05.330 --> 00:24:07.430 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So [INAUDIBLE]
really sharp up

00:24:07.430 --> 00:24:09.660 align:middle line:84%
to the delta to
the epsilon factor?

00:24:09.660 --> 00:24:11.520 align:middle line:84%
LARRY GUTH: Yeah,
it's sharp up to this.

00:24:11.520 --> 00:24:16.620 align:middle line:84%
So it's sharp up to the
delta to the epsilon.

00:24:16.620 --> 00:24:17.190 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

00:24:17.190 --> 00:24:21.810 align:middle line:84%
In the future, I'm going to
abbreviate that mess by this

00:24:21.810 --> 00:24:24.525 align:middle line:84%
because we won't be at the level
of detail to have all of this

00:24:24.525 --> 00:24:25.025 align:middle line:90%
anyway.

00:24:25.025 --> 00:24:32.908 align:middle line:90%


00:24:32.908 --> 00:24:35.620 align:middle line:84%
So the story I wanted
to try to tell,

00:24:35.620 --> 00:24:37.830 align:middle line:84%
to explore over the
last three classes,

00:24:37.830 --> 00:24:41.580 align:middle line:84%
is how is it possible to get
from these epsilon improvements

00:24:41.580 --> 00:24:44.130 align:middle line:90%
to sharp theorems?

00:24:44.130 --> 00:24:48.870 align:middle line:84%
That's our theme for
the rest of the class.

00:24:48.870 --> 00:24:54.150 align:middle line:84%
And if I had to say it in
a couple of sentences, what

00:24:54.150 --> 00:24:56.460 align:middle line:84%
happened was people
found a way where

00:24:56.460 --> 00:24:59.170 align:middle line:84%
you can use an epsilon
improvement theorem,

00:24:59.170 --> 00:25:01.500 align:middle line:84%
and you can use it
over and over again.

00:25:01.500 --> 00:25:04.110 align:middle line:84%
And each time you
use it, you improve

00:25:04.110 --> 00:25:06.090 align:middle line:84%
a little bit the
exponent in your bound

00:25:06.090 --> 00:25:10.600 align:middle line:84%
until you bring the exponent
up to the sharp value.

00:25:10.600 --> 00:25:12.693 align:middle line:84%
Now, it's not at all
obvious how to do that.

00:25:12.693 --> 00:25:14.110 align:middle line:84%
And that's what
we're going to try

00:25:14.110 --> 00:25:18.650 align:middle line:84%
to explain, not
with all details,

00:25:18.650 --> 00:25:21.610 align:middle line:84%
but to make it seem like
a plausible approach

00:25:21.610 --> 00:25:23.160 align:middle line:90%
that you could carry out.

00:25:23.160 --> 00:25:26.180 align:middle line:90%


00:25:26.180 --> 00:25:28.130 align:middle line:84%
So any questions or
comments before we start?

00:25:28.130 --> 00:25:28.630 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:25:28.630 --> 00:25:30.070 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Does
doing that process

00:25:30.070 --> 00:25:34.390 align:middle line:84%
make the C [INAUDIBLE] constant
kind of correspondingly,

00:25:34.390 --> 00:25:38.425 align:middle line:84%
I guess, tiny compared
to the epsilon constant?

00:25:38.425 --> 00:25:40.300 align:middle line:84%
LARRY GUTH: Yeah, so I
think the question is,

00:25:40.300 --> 00:25:43.730 align:middle line:84%
as we use our epsilon
improvement theorem many times,

00:25:43.730 --> 00:25:47.020 align:middle line:84%
does that cause this to
become remarkably bad?

00:25:47.020 --> 00:25:48.580 align:middle line:90%
I think it does.

00:25:48.580 --> 00:25:50.330 align:middle line:84%
I think that this
is remarkably bad.

00:25:50.330 --> 00:25:54.430 align:middle line:90%


00:25:54.430 --> 00:25:55.730 align:middle line:90%
OK, great.

00:25:55.730 --> 00:26:00.550 align:middle line:84%
So today, my first goal is I
want to describe the simplest

00:26:00.550 --> 00:26:04.030 align:middle line:90%
example where you can get--

00:26:04.030 --> 00:26:05.890 align:middle line:84%
where you can use an
epsilon improvement

00:26:05.890 --> 00:26:09.070 align:middle line:84%
theorem to prove
a sharp theorem.

00:26:09.070 --> 00:26:10.910 align:middle line:84%
And then after that,
if we have time,

00:26:10.910 --> 00:26:14.680 align:middle line:84%
I will outline the proof
of the big theorem.

00:26:14.680 --> 00:26:15.180 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:26:15.180 --> 00:26:53.320 align:middle line:90%


00:26:53.320 --> 00:27:06.890 align:middle line:84%
So simplest example
where epsilon improvement

00:27:06.890 --> 00:27:09.150 align:middle line:90%
leads to sharp out.

00:27:09.150 --> 00:27:13.910 align:middle line:90%


00:27:13.910 --> 00:27:20.690 align:middle line:84%
So this is a theorem of
Beck from around 1980, which

00:27:20.690 --> 00:27:23.130 align:middle line:84%
is about the incidences
of points and lines.

00:27:23.130 --> 00:27:26.450 align:middle line:84%
So it's in the setting of the
Szemerédi--Trotter theorem.

00:27:26.450 --> 00:27:30.920 align:middle line:84%
So it says, if E
is a subset of R2--

00:27:30.920 --> 00:27:33.060 align:middle line:90%
and it's not all on a line.

00:27:33.060 --> 00:27:35.870 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, I'll say at
most half of it is on a line.

00:27:35.870 --> 00:27:45.080 align:middle line:84%
So for any line L, L intersects
E is at most half of it.

00:27:45.080 --> 00:27:50.810 align:middle line:84%
Then, the conclusion is there
exists some point x in E

00:27:50.810 --> 00:27:52.610 align:middle line:90%
so that--

00:27:52.610 --> 00:27:54.450 align:middle line:84%
all right, so let me
make a definition.

00:27:54.450 --> 00:27:55.650 align:middle line:90%
So I'll draw a picture.

00:27:55.650 --> 00:28:03.330 align:middle line:84%
So this is E. So there's
our set E. Here's a point x.

00:28:03.330 --> 00:28:08.340 align:middle line:84%
Starting at x, I will draw
all the lines that start at x

00:28:08.340 --> 00:28:15.820 align:middle line:84%
and go through some other
points at E. So what's that set?

00:28:15.820 --> 00:28:18.180 align:middle line:90%
So I'll call it LxE.

00:28:18.180 --> 00:28:22.620 align:middle line:84%
So this is the set of
lines so that lines L--

00:28:22.620 --> 00:28:28.240 align:middle line:84%
so that x is in L, and L
intersect E is not just x,

00:28:28.240 --> 00:28:29.920 align:middle line:90%
so it has size at least 2.

00:28:29.920 --> 00:28:33.900 align:middle line:90%


00:28:33.900 --> 00:28:38.790 align:middle line:84%
Conclusion is there is a point
in E so that the size of LxE

00:28:38.790 --> 00:28:47.910 align:middle line:90%
is comparable to the size of E.

00:28:47.910 --> 00:28:50.190 align:middle line:84%
This is clearly a sharp
theorem because the largest

00:28:50.190 --> 00:28:56.130 align:middle line:84%
possible size that this
could be is the size of E.

00:28:56.130 --> 00:28:57.395 align:middle line:90%
Let me do a proof sketch.

00:28:57.395 --> 00:29:01.110 align:middle line:90%


00:29:01.110 --> 00:29:04.120 align:middle line:84%
And we'll-- so we'll see
that this follows from

00:29:04.120 --> 00:29:05.650 align:middle line:90%
Szemerédi--Trotter.

00:29:05.650 --> 00:29:09.190 align:middle line:84%
But we'll also see that we don't
really need the sharp exponents

00:29:09.190 --> 00:29:10.330 align:middle line:90%
in Szemerédi--Trotter.

00:29:10.330 --> 00:29:16.960 align:middle line:84%
We just need to have something
that's an epsilon better than a

00:29:16.960 --> 00:29:17.900 align:middle line:90%
simple bound.

00:29:17.900 --> 00:29:20.290 align:middle line:84%
That's why I've erased it,
but than the double counting

00:29:20.290 --> 00:29:23.350 align:middle line:90%
kind of bound.

00:29:23.350 --> 00:29:24.470 align:middle line:90%
So here we go.

00:29:24.470 --> 00:29:26.710 align:middle line:84%
So the sketchy part
of my proof sketch

00:29:26.710 --> 00:29:30.080 align:middle line:84%
is that I will suppose that
we are in the uniform case.

00:29:30.080 --> 00:29:34.690 align:middle line:84%
Namely, for every x in E,
I will suppose that Lx of E

00:29:34.690 --> 00:29:38.770 align:middle line:90%
has size around x.

00:29:38.770 --> 00:29:41.720 align:middle line:84%
So it's not really the case that
they would all be comparable,

00:29:41.720 --> 00:29:45.880 align:middle line:84%
but I'll just explain
that special case.

00:29:45.880 --> 00:29:49.990 align:middle line:84%
So now, how many lines
are there in total?

00:29:49.990 --> 00:29:54.280 align:middle line:84%
We can do a double count to
find the total number of lines.

00:29:54.280 --> 00:30:03.970 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to double count
pairs xL where x is in E,

00:30:03.970 --> 00:30:08.920 align:middle line:90%
and L is in our set of lines.

00:30:08.920 --> 00:30:12.015 align:middle line:84%
So our total set of
lines is going to be--

00:30:12.015 --> 00:30:16.408 align:middle line:90%


00:30:16.408 --> 00:30:17.450 align:middle line:90%
all right, let's do this.

00:30:17.450 --> 00:30:21.320 align:middle line:90%


00:30:21.320 --> 00:30:23.350 align:middle line:90%
So how big is LE?

00:30:23.350 --> 00:30:27.350 align:middle line:84%
Well, we could count the number
of these pairs in two ways.

00:30:27.350 --> 00:30:31.660 align:middle line:84%
We could count-- look at all the
points of E, and each of them

00:30:31.660 --> 00:30:33.880 align:middle line:90%
is in S lines.

00:30:33.880 --> 00:30:37.780 align:middle line:84%
Or we could say, look
at each of these lines,

00:30:37.780 --> 00:30:41.660 align:middle line:84%
and how many points
are in each line?

00:30:41.660 --> 00:30:48.670 align:middle line:84%
Well, the number
of the size of S--

00:30:48.670 --> 00:30:54.580 align:middle line:84%
the size of E intersect
L for a typical L and LxE

00:30:54.580 --> 00:31:00.090 align:middle line:84%
would be the size of E
divided by the size of LxE.

00:31:00.090 --> 00:31:01.950 align:middle line:84%
So I have all the
points in E. They are

00:31:01.950 --> 00:31:04.380 align:middle line:90%
divided among the lines of LxE.

00:31:04.380 --> 00:31:06.570 align:middle line:84%
Again, assuming it's
uniform, they would all

00:31:06.570 --> 00:31:08.150 align:middle line:90%
have around this size--

00:31:08.150 --> 00:31:11.910 align:middle line:90%


00:31:11.910 --> 00:31:23.100 align:middle line:90%
E over LxE, which is S.

00:31:23.100 --> 00:31:27.630 align:middle line:84%
So this is the number of points
times they're each in S lines

00:31:27.630 --> 00:31:33.340 align:middle line:84%
versus the number of lines times
they each have this many points.

00:31:33.340 --> 00:31:36.850 align:middle line:84%
So when we solve, we see that
the E actually drops out.

00:31:36.850 --> 00:31:41.225 align:middle line:84%
And we conclude that
LE is around S squared.

00:31:41.225 --> 00:31:47.844 align:middle line:90%


00:31:47.844 --> 00:31:51.670 align:middle line:84%
So our goal is to have
a lower bound on S.

00:31:51.670 --> 00:31:54.180 align:middle line:84%
So we want to have
a lower bound on LE.

00:31:54.180 --> 00:31:57.000 align:middle line:84%
And the Szemerédi--Trotter
theorem exactly gives us a lower

00:31:57.000 --> 00:31:59.500 align:middle line:90%
bound on LE, so we can use it.

00:31:59.500 --> 00:32:04.770 align:middle line:84%
So the Szemerédi--Trotter
theorem tells us that LE is

00:32:04.770 --> 00:32:12.420 align:middle line:84%
at least the minimum of S times
E and S to the 3/2 times E

00:32:12.420 --> 00:32:15.390 align:middle line:90%
to the 1/2.

00:32:15.390 --> 00:32:18.220 align:middle line:90%
But this LE is S squared.

00:32:18.220 --> 00:32:24.450 align:middle line:84%
So if you compare these, we
can get a lower bound for S.

00:32:24.450 --> 00:32:28.110 align:middle line:84%
In this case, we would have
S squared is bigger than SE.

00:32:28.110 --> 00:32:31.090 align:middle line:84%
So S is bigger than
E. And in this case,

00:32:31.090 --> 00:32:33.780 align:middle line:84%
we would have S squared is
bigger than S to the 3/2 E

00:32:33.780 --> 00:32:35.190 align:middle line:90%
to the 1/2.

00:32:35.190 --> 00:32:48.750 align:middle line:84%
And with a little algebra, that
is, again, S bigger than E. OK.

00:32:48.750 --> 00:32:53.890 align:middle line:90%


00:32:53.890 --> 00:32:56.405 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:32:56.405 --> 00:32:56.905 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:32:56.905 --> 00:33:01.450 align:middle line:90%


00:33:01.450 --> 00:33:05.410 align:middle line:84%
Now, I claimed that
we didn't need to have

00:33:05.410 --> 00:33:07.150 align:middle line:90%
this exact formula here.

00:33:07.150 --> 00:33:10.240 align:middle line:84%
Let me write down all
that we needed to know.

00:33:10.240 --> 00:33:16.570 align:middle line:84%
So what we needed
to know is just

00:33:16.570 --> 00:33:24.850 align:middle line:84%
that, if E is much bigger
than S, then the size of LE

00:33:24.850 --> 00:33:26.775 align:middle line:90%
is much bigger than S squared.

00:33:26.775 --> 00:33:30.430 align:middle line:90%


00:33:30.430 --> 00:33:33.470 align:middle line:84%
So that's a feature you can
read off of this formula.

00:33:33.470 --> 00:33:35.800 align:middle line:84%
If E is much bigger than
S, then either one of these

00:33:35.800 --> 00:33:37.660 align:middle line:90%
is much bigger than S squared.

00:33:37.660 --> 00:33:39.850 align:middle line:84%
And that's all we needed
to know because we

00:33:39.850 --> 00:33:42.260 align:middle line:90%
know that LE is only S squared.

00:33:42.260 --> 00:33:44.170 align:middle line:84%
So by the
contrapositive, we could

00:33:44.170 --> 00:33:48.430 align:middle line:84%
see that S is not
much smaller than ES.

00:33:48.430 --> 00:33:52.840 align:middle line:90%
It should be at least around E.

00:33:52.840 --> 00:33:56.680 align:middle line:84%
So this thing that
we needed to know

00:33:56.680 --> 00:34:00.315 align:middle line:84%
is very similar to the
Orponen-Shmerkin theorem.

00:34:00.315 --> 00:34:03.270 align:middle line:90%


00:34:03.270 --> 00:34:04.550 align:middle line:90%
E is much bigger.

00:34:04.550 --> 00:34:09.699 align:middle line:84%
So now let's look up at that
Orponen-Shmerkin theorem, says,

00:34:09.699 --> 00:34:14.290 align:middle line:84%
if T is bigger than S,
which is bigger than 0--

00:34:14.290 --> 00:34:17.380 align:middle line:84%
so T is measuring the
size of our set E,

00:34:17.380 --> 00:34:21.280 align:middle line:84%
and little S
corresponds to big S.

00:34:21.280 --> 00:34:23.770 align:middle line:84%
So that first
hypothesis is saying

00:34:23.770 --> 00:34:28.060 align:middle line:84%
that the set is much bigger
than the number of directions.

00:34:28.060 --> 00:34:30.850 align:middle line:84%
And then the conclusion is
that the number of lines

00:34:30.850 --> 00:34:32.920 align:middle line:90%
is much bigger than S squared.

00:34:32.920 --> 00:34:34.670 align:middle line:90%
That thing is this thing.

00:34:34.670 --> 00:34:38.320 align:middle line:90%


00:34:38.320 --> 00:34:45.699 align:middle line:84%
So this matches the theorem
of Orponen and Shmerkin,

00:34:45.699 --> 00:34:47.249 align:middle line:90%
the epsilon improvement theorem.

00:34:47.249 --> 00:34:53.199 align:middle line:90%


00:34:53.199 --> 00:34:56.989 align:middle line:84%
So that suggests an
idea that we could

00:34:56.989 --> 00:35:00.440 align:middle line:84%
use that epsilon improvement
theorem by Orponen and Shmerkin

00:35:00.440 --> 00:35:03.150 align:middle line:84%
and put it into an
argument like this one

00:35:03.150 --> 00:35:06.410 align:middle line:84%
and prove some kind of
generalization of Beck's theorem

00:35:06.410 --> 00:35:11.900 align:middle line:84%
that might have a sharp
conclusion, even though we stuck

00:35:11.900 --> 00:35:15.320 align:middle line:84%
into it just an
epsilon improvement.

00:35:15.320 --> 00:35:16.950 align:middle line:90%
And that actually works.

00:35:16.950 --> 00:36:01.050 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to write
it down now for us

00:36:01.050 --> 00:36:04.440 align:middle line:90%
So this is called the continuum.

00:36:04.440 --> 00:36:07.170 align:middle line:84%
Or we could call it in
our class the delta ball

00:36:07.170 --> 00:36:08.770 align:middle line:90%
version of Beck's theorem.

00:36:08.770 --> 00:36:15.320 align:middle line:90%


00:36:15.320 --> 00:36:19.170 align:middle line:84%
So this is a theorem of
Orponen, Shmerkin, and Wang,

00:36:19.170 --> 00:36:23.770 align:middle line:90%
in '23, I think.

00:36:23.770 --> 00:36:26.220 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to translate
this theorem into the language

00:36:26.220 --> 00:36:28.560 align:middle line:90%
of delta S, C sets.

00:36:28.560 --> 00:36:34.020 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to say,
if E is a delta, u set--

00:36:34.020 --> 00:36:37.990 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to leave out the
C. Things will depend on C.

00:36:37.990 --> 00:36:41.490 align:middle line:90%
But E is a delta, u set.

00:36:41.490 --> 00:36:42.970 align:middle line:90%
So that's our set.

00:36:42.970 --> 00:36:45.840 align:middle line:84%
Now I need an analog
of this hypothesis

00:36:45.840 --> 00:36:48.490 align:middle line:84%
that E is not too
much in the line.

00:36:48.490 --> 00:36:51.400 align:middle line:84%
And the analog says
that E will be not too

00:36:51.400 --> 00:36:53.590 align:middle line:90%
much in any thin rectangle.

00:36:53.590 --> 00:37:04.180 align:middle line:84%
So we'll say if R is a rho by 1
rectangle, then if you take E,

00:37:04.180 --> 00:37:07.480 align:middle line:84%
and you intersect it with R,
take the delta-covering number

00:37:07.480 --> 00:37:12.520 align:middle line:84%
of that, that should
be kind of smaller

00:37:12.520 --> 00:37:16.340 align:middle line:84%
than the total
delta-covering number

00:37:16.340 --> 00:37:19.060 align:middle line:84%
So it should be rho to the A
to smaller than constant rho

00:37:19.060 --> 00:37:21.560 align:middle line:84%
to the A to smaller than the
total delta-covering number.

00:37:21.560 --> 00:37:23.630 align:middle line:84%
Maybe we can put
this back here also.

00:37:23.630 --> 00:37:25.010 align:middle line:90%
So who is eta?

00:37:25.010 --> 00:37:26.750 align:middle line:84%
At the very beginning
of this story,

00:37:26.750 --> 00:37:31.210 align:middle line:84%
we'll say, for every
eta bigger than 0.

00:37:31.210 --> 00:37:33.600 align:middle line:84%
So eta should be
a positive number.

00:37:33.600 --> 00:37:36.590 align:middle line:84%
So this is not super
strong condition,

00:37:36.590 --> 00:37:39.400 align:middle line:84%
but it's saying that E is
not heavily concentrated

00:37:39.400 --> 00:37:42.220 align:middle line:90%
into a thin rectangle

00:37:42.220 --> 00:37:49.030 align:middle line:84%
Then the conclusion is
there exists an x in E

00:37:49.030 --> 00:37:56.980 align:middle line:84%
so that the size
of LxE is greater

00:37:56.980 --> 00:38:05.600 align:middle line:84%
than the minimum of delta
to the minus u and 1.

00:38:05.600 --> 00:38:07.180 align:middle line:90%
So this would be--

00:38:07.180 --> 00:38:10.360 align:middle line:84%
sorry, not 1, delta
to the minus 1.

00:38:10.360 --> 00:38:12.230 align:middle line:90%
So what's going on here?

00:38:12.230 --> 00:38:15.040 align:middle line:84%
Our original theorem
would say that E

00:38:15.040 --> 00:38:18.170 align:middle line:84%
is at least the size of E.
And that's the size of E,

00:38:18.170 --> 00:38:20.020 align:middle line:90%
so that's what it's doing here.

00:38:20.020 --> 00:38:23.450 align:middle line:84%
On the other hand, if I
had every delta tube--

00:38:23.450 --> 00:38:26.270 align:middle line:84%
if LxE consisted of all
the delta tubes through x,

00:38:26.270 --> 00:38:28.280 align:middle line:84%
there would only be
delta inverse of them.

00:38:28.280 --> 00:38:30.650 align:middle line:84%
So it couldn't possibly
be bigger than this.

00:38:30.650 --> 00:38:34.265 align:middle line:90%
So we have it.

00:38:34.265 --> 00:38:34.765 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:38:34.765 --> 00:38:37.630 align:middle line:90%


00:38:37.630 --> 00:38:38.420 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:38:38.420 --> 00:38:40.280 align:middle line:84%
So that's the statement
of the theorem.

00:38:40.280 --> 00:38:45.210 align:middle line:84%
And it is, again, sharp
because as we just explained,

00:38:45.210 --> 00:38:47.550 align:middle line:84%
this couldn't possibly
be bigger than this,

00:38:47.550 --> 00:38:50.050 align:middle line:84%
and it also couldn't
possibly be bigger than this.

00:38:50.050 --> 00:39:07.130 align:middle line:90%


00:39:07.130 --> 00:39:08.610 align:middle line:90%
So this theorem is sharp.

00:39:08.610 --> 00:39:17.540 align:middle line:84%
It's also false over C.
So the example over C

00:39:17.540 --> 00:39:25.460 align:middle line:84%
would be that the set E could
be R2, which is sitting in C2.

00:39:25.460 --> 00:39:28.880 align:middle line:84%
And if you imagine R2, if
you take any point in R2,

00:39:28.880 --> 00:39:33.230 align:middle line:84%
and look at all of the lines,
complex lines that go through

00:39:33.230 --> 00:39:37.010 align:middle line:90%
that point, there aren't--

00:39:37.010 --> 00:39:40.170 align:middle line:84%
each one of them goes through
many of the points of R2.

00:39:40.170 --> 00:39:44.080 align:middle line:84%
And the number-- there
aren't that many of them.

00:39:44.080 --> 00:39:45.050 align:middle line:90%
It would violate this.

00:39:45.050 --> 00:39:49.420 align:middle line:90%


00:39:49.420 --> 00:39:54.240 align:middle line:84%
So this theorem is in the
general spirit of projection

00:39:54.240 --> 00:39:57.430 align:middle line:90%
theory, it is a sharp theorem.

00:39:57.430 --> 00:40:00.240 align:middle line:84%
And it distinguishes
R from C. And I

00:40:00.240 --> 00:40:02.980 align:middle line:84%
believe it is the first such
theorem in the literature.

00:40:02.980 --> 00:40:07.020 align:middle line:84%
So we were trying for 20-plus
years to distinguish R from C.

00:40:07.020 --> 00:40:10.300 align:middle line:84%
For a long time, we could only
do it with epsilon improvements.

00:40:10.300 --> 00:40:12.360 align:middle line:84%
But this is not just
an epsilon improvement

00:40:12.360 --> 00:40:13.830 align:middle line:90%
on what was known before.

00:40:13.830 --> 00:40:15.330 align:middle line:84%
It's not just an
epsilon improvement

00:40:15.330 --> 00:40:20.820 align:middle line:84%
on what's true over C
And it's a sharp theorem.

00:40:20.820 --> 00:40:24.690 align:middle line:84%
Any questions or comments
about the statement?

00:40:24.690 --> 00:40:28.710 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So the
[INAUDIBLE] depends on eta?

00:40:28.710 --> 00:40:31.710 align:middle line:84%
LARRY GUTH: Yeah, so
if you unpack this,

00:40:31.710 --> 00:40:34.170 align:middle line:90%
it must depend on eta.

00:40:34.170 --> 00:40:39.340 align:middle line:84%
I think it is a constant
depending on epsilon and an eta,

00:40:39.340 --> 00:40:45.370 align:middle line:84%
delta to the epsilon, and
big C to the minus big 1.

00:40:45.370 --> 00:40:47.110 align:middle line:90%
So it depends on eta.

00:40:47.110 --> 00:40:50.680 align:middle line:90%


00:40:50.680 --> 00:40:52.988 align:middle line:84%
It's conceivable that
this depends on eta.

00:40:52.988 --> 00:40:53.530 align:middle line:90%
I'm not sure.

00:40:53.530 --> 00:41:03.640 align:middle line:90%


00:41:03.640 --> 00:41:04.995 align:middle line:90%
Other questions or comments?

00:41:04.995 --> 00:41:13.670 align:middle line:90%


00:41:13.670 --> 00:41:19.450 align:middle line:84%
So the idea in the first
place is to imitate this proof

00:41:19.450 --> 00:41:27.580 align:middle line:84%
of Beck's theorem, proof that
converts an epsilon improvement

00:41:27.580 --> 00:41:30.670 align:middle line:84%
on some simple estimate for
Szemerédi--Trotter into a sharp

00:41:30.670 --> 00:41:33.760 align:middle line:84%
estimate for this
Beck kind of thing.

00:41:33.760 --> 00:41:35.830 align:middle line:84%
But when we try to
do that, we will see

00:41:35.830 --> 00:41:38.410 align:middle line:90%
that there is an issue with it.

00:41:38.410 --> 00:41:41.600 align:middle line:84%
And when we flesh out
the proof a little more,

00:41:41.600 --> 00:41:45.130 align:middle line:84%
it will involve using the
Orponen-Shmerkin theorem not

00:41:45.130 --> 00:41:48.000 align:middle line:84%
just once, but many times
at many different scales.

00:41:48.000 --> 00:41:51.440 align:middle line:90%


00:41:51.440 --> 00:41:53.055 align:middle line:90%
So let's sketch the proof.

00:41:53.055 --> 00:41:56.020 align:middle line:90%


00:41:56.020 --> 00:42:07.230 align:middle line:84%
So the first plan is to
imitate the proof of Beck.

00:42:07.230 --> 00:42:10.790 align:middle line:90%


00:42:10.790 --> 00:42:12.970 align:middle line:84%
So let's carry
that out over here,

00:42:12.970 --> 00:42:14.775 align:middle line:90%
I'll put the Beck's proof up.

00:42:14.775 --> 00:42:42.710 align:middle line:90%


00:42:42.710 --> 00:42:45.580 align:middle line:90%
So attempt one.

00:42:45.580 --> 00:42:49.920 align:middle line:90%


00:42:49.920 --> 00:42:58.013 align:middle line:84%
So let's say that LxE
is a delta S, C set.

00:42:58.013 --> 00:43:01.070 align:middle line:90%


00:43:01.070 --> 00:43:05.310 align:middle line:84%
Now, that's related to
the cardinality of LxE.

00:43:05.310 --> 00:43:07.970 align:middle line:84%
This is a theorem about
the cardinality of LxE.

00:43:07.970 --> 00:43:09.450 align:middle line:90%
What is the relationship?

00:43:09.450 --> 00:43:13.190 align:middle line:84%
Well, it implies that
the cardinality of LxE

00:43:13.190 --> 00:43:17.840 align:middle line:84%
is at least around
delta to the minus S,

00:43:17.840 --> 00:43:19.375 align:middle line:90%
but it could be much bigger.

00:43:19.375 --> 00:43:26.300 align:middle line:90%


00:43:26.300 --> 00:43:29.630 align:middle line:84%
So an example where these would
be about the same as if LxE

00:43:29.630 --> 00:43:32.430 align:middle line:84%
was like an
S-dimensional Cantor set.

00:43:32.430 --> 00:43:35.610 align:middle line:84%
An example where they
would be very different

00:43:35.610 --> 00:43:39.580 align:middle line:90%
is if LxE was very clumped.

00:43:39.580 --> 00:43:47.370 align:middle line:84%
So here's a piece of S1, and
maybe LxE is clumped like that.

00:43:47.370 --> 00:43:48.870 align:middle line:90%
So these dots represent LxE.

00:43:48.870 --> 00:43:51.930 align:middle line:90%


00:43:51.930 --> 00:43:56.770 align:middle line:84%
So if LxE was really clumped
into a much smaller interval,

00:43:56.770 --> 00:44:01.410 align:middle line:84%
then the S would
actually have to be 0.

00:44:01.410 --> 00:44:06.270 align:middle line:84%
This is not a delta S, C
set, except for S equals 0.

00:44:06.270 --> 00:44:08.520 align:middle line:84%
On the other hand,
the cardinality

00:44:08.520 --> 00:44:12.810 align:middle line:90%
of LxE in this picture is large.

00:44:12.810 --> 00:44:15.120 align:middle line:84%
And in particular, it's
much larger than delta

00:44:15.120 --> 00:44:16.175 align:middle line:90%
to the minus 0.

00:44:16.175 --> 00:44:20.570 align:middle line:90%


00:44:20.570 --> 00:44:24.820 align:middle line:84%
So this S is some
non-concentration condition.

00:44:24.820 --> 00:44:28.330 align:middle line:84%
And non-concentration forces
are set to be pretty big.

00:44:28.330 --> 00:44:30.580 align:middle line:84%
But it could also be
much bigger than that

00:44:30.580 --> 00:44:32.175 align:middle line:90%
if it was kind of clumped.

00:44:32.175 --> 00:44:35.692 align:middle line:90%


00:44:35.692 --> 00:44:40.660 align:middle line:84%
So let's try to
imitate our proof.

00:44:40.660 --> 00:44:44.200 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to suppose that
we're in the uniform case.

00:44:44.200 --> 00:44:56.630 align:middle line:84%
So all of the LxE have the
same S and the same size of LxE

00:44:56.630 --> 00:44:58.560 align:middle line:84%
We can do our same
double counting.

00:44:58.560 --> 00:45:02.770 align:middle line:90%


00:45:02.770 --> 00:45:04.760 align:middle line:90%
That part doesn't change at all.

00:45:04.760 --> 00:45:11.533 align:middle line:84%
And it gives us LE is
at least LxE squared.

00:45:11.533 --> 00:45:14.290 align:middle line:90%


00:45:14.290 --> 00:45:15.610 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:45:15.610 --> 00:45:17.550 align:middle line:84%
Sorry, is approximately
LxE squared.

00:45:17.550 --> 00:45:21.370 align:middle line:90%


00:45:21.370 --> 00:45:23.680 align:middle line:84%
And so to get a
lower bound on LxE,

00:45:23.680 --> 00:45:25.940 align:middle line:84%
it suffices to get
a lower bound on LE.

00:45:25.940 --> 00:45:28.540 align:middle line:90%


00:45:28.540 --> 00:45:30.010 align:middle line:90%
So what happens here?

00:45:30.010 --> 00:45:35.980 align:middle line:84%
So now we can apply the theorem
of Orponen-Shmerkin, the epsilon

00:45:35.980 --> 00:45:41.530 align:middle line:84%
improvement, which I just
erased in a suboptimal use

00:45:41.530 --> 00:45:43.120 align:middle line:90%
of blackboards.

00:45:43.120 --> 00:45:47.920 align:middle line:84%
But what it says in
this case is that,

00:45:47.920 --> 00:45:57.010 align:middle line:84%
if S is smaller than the minimum
of u and 1, but bigger than 0,

00:45:57.010 --> 00:46:07.000 align:middle line:84%
then we get LE is at least delta
to the minus 2S minus epsilon.

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:10.450 align:middle line:84%
So this would be
the classical bound.

00:46:10.450 --> 00:46:11.460 align:middle line:90%
And then we have this.

00:46:11.460 --> 00:46:15.920 align:middle line:90%


00:46:15.920 --> 00:46:17.800 align:middle line:84%
And then we're
interested in LxE.

00:46:17.800 --> 00:46:23.710 align:middle line:84%
That tells us that LxE is at
least delta to the minus S

00:46:23.710 --> 00:46:24.630 align:middle line:90%
minus epsilon.

00:46:24.630 --> 00:46:36.720 align:middle line:90%


00:46:36.720 --> 00:46:39.890 align:middle line:90%
So let's take stock.

00:46:39.890 --> 00:46:43.290 align:middle line:84%
If S were equal to the
minimum of u and 1,

00:46:43.290 --> 00:46:46.260 align:middle line:84%
then LxE would be at least
delta to the minus S.

00:46:46.260 --> 00:46:48.240 align:middle line:84%
That would be the
bound we want to prove.

00:46:48.240 --> 00:46:49.945 align:middle line:84%
So in that case, we
would be very happy.

00:46:49.945 --> 00:46:52.980 align:middle line:90%


00:46:52.980 --> 00:46:55.230 align:middle line:90%
Now suppose S is in this range.

00:46:55.230 --> 00:46:57.740 align:middle line:90%
Well, then we get this bound.

00:46:57.740 --> 00:47:00.970 align:middle line:84%
This bound is a tiny bit
better than this bound.

00:47:00.970 --> 00:47:04.070 align:middle line:90%


00:47:04.070 --> 00:47:05.050 align:middle line:90%
But that's all.

00:47:05.050 --> 00:47:07.820 align:middle line:90%


00:47:07.820 --> 00:47:11.600 align:middle line:84%
This argument didn't work
so nicely as that argument,

00:47:11.600 --> 00:47:15.260 align:middle line:84%
because in that case,
there was no distinction

00:47:15.260 --> 00:47:19.910 align:middle line:84%
between cardinality and the
value of S. In that case, this

00:47:19.910 --> 00:47:21.360 align:middle line:90%
was the same as this.

00:47:21.360 --> 00:47:23.370 align:middle line:84%
So we would get a
contradiction at this moment.

00:47:23.370 --> 00:47:25.380 align:middle line:84%
And we could conclude
that, actually, S

00:47:25.380 --> 00:47:27.500 align:middle line:90%
is the minimum of u and 1.

00:47:27.500 --> 00:47:35.550 align:middle line:90%


00:47:35.550 --> 00:47:37.380 align:middle line:90%
So we did learned something.

00:47:37.380 --> 00:47:40.050 align:middle line:90%


00:47:40.050 --> 00:47:45.480 align:middle line:84%
If LxE were kind of spread
out, then you might hope that

00:47:45.480 --> 00:47:48.840 align:middle line:84%
the cardinality would be
about delta to the minus S.

00:47:48.840 --> 00:47:53.070 align:middle line:84%
And in that spread-out
case, then we could get--

00:47:53.070 --> 00:47:58.350 align:middle line:84%
it would follow that S
the minimum of u and 1.

00:47:58.350 --> 00:48:08.130 align:middle line:84%
So we see this corollary
if LxE is a delta,

00:48:08.130 --> 00:48:15.640 align:middle line:84%
S set, and the size of LxE is
around delta to the minus S.

00:48:15.640 --> 00:48:18.540 align:middle line:84%
Then we would get
that the size of LxE

00:48:18.540 --> 00:48:21.750 align:middle line:84%
is greater than around
the minimum of delta

00:48:21.750 --> 00:48:26.620 align:middle line:84%
to the minus u and delta to the
minus 1, and we would be happy.

00:48:26.620 --> 00:48:29.590 align:middle line:90%
But it's a big if.

00:48:29.590 --> 00:48:31.450 align:middle line:84%
And we don't understand
yet very well

00:48:31.450 --> 00:48:35.100 align:middle line:84%
what might happen if these sets
were a little more clumped.

00:48:35.100 --> 00:48:38.610 align:middle line:90%


00:48:38.610 --> 00:48:39.110 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:48:39.110 --> 00:48:44.870 align:middle line:90%


00:48:44.870 --> 00:48:49.840 align:middle line:84%
So let me put up a summary
of what we've learned so far.

00:48:49.840 --> 00:49:03.970 align:middle line:84%
So lemma-- if S is bigger than
0, and a typical LxE is delta,

00:49:03.970 --> 00:49:13.930 align:middle line:84%
S, C, then size of a typical LxE
is at least delta to the minus S

00:49:13.930 --> 00:49:15.280 align:middle line:90%
minus epsilon--

00:49:15.280 --> 00:49:19.960 align:middle line:84%
or sorry, yeah, if
0 is less than S,

00:49:19.960 --> 00:49:22.790 align:middle line:84%
is less than the
minimum of u, 1.

00:49:22.790 --> 00:49:26.210 align:middle line:90%


00:49:26.210 --> 00:49:28.730 align:middle line:84%
So the proof of this theorem,
we don't have it yet.

00:49:28.730 --> 00:49:30.280 align:middle line:90%
We have this lemma.

00:49:30.280 --> 00:49:33.280 align:middle line:84%
The proof of this theorem is,
by bootstrapping this lemma,

00:49:33.280 --> 00:49:36.530 align:middle line:84%
using it many times at
different scales and locations.

00:49:36.530 --> 00:49:39.580 align:middle line:84%
So we are, effectively,
using the epsilon improvement

00:49:39.580 --> 00:49:42.210 align:middle line:84%
many times, not just
once, and at many scales.

00:49:42.210 --> 00:50:18.380 align:middle line:90%


00:50:18.380 --> 00:50:23.280 align:middle line:84%
So let's do a sketch of
this bootstrap iteration.

00:50:23.280 --> 00:50:35.145 align:middle line:90%


00:50:35.145 --> 00:50:45.320 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to suppose that
LxE, first of all, is uniform

00:50:45.320 --> 00:50:50.630 align:middle line:84%
and also that it is
delta S, C for some S

00:50:50.630 --> 00:50:52.640 align:middle line:90%
which is bigger than 0.

00:50:52.640 --> 00:50:56.210 align:middle line:90%
It's the start of our bootstrap.

00:50:56.210 --> 00:50:58.760 align:middle line:84%
So because it's uniform,
and it's a delta,

00:50:58.760 --> 00:51:03.650 align:middle line:84%
S, C set, then it follows
that, if you take its rho

00:51:03.650 --> 00:51:11.120 align:middle line:84%
neighborhood, then this is a
rho, S, C set for every rho.

00:51:11.120 --> 00:51:14.720 align:middle line:90%
And now we can apply our lemma.

00:51:14.720 --> 00:51:18.720 align:middle line:84%
And the lemma tells us that
the cardinality of LxE,

00:51:18.720 --> 00:51:25.800 align:middle line:84%
the rho-covering number of LxE,
is at least rho to the minus S

00:51:25.800 --> 00:51:27.000 align:middle line:90%
minus epsilon.

00:51:27.000 --> 00:51:30.570 align:middle line:84%
So rho to the minus S is what
we get just from being a rho,

00:51:30.570 --> 00:51:31.630 align:middle line:90%
S, C set.

00:51:31.630 --> 00:51:34.050 align:middle line:84%
But actually, it has to be a
little bit bigger than that

00:51:34.050 --> 00:51:35.910 align:middle line:90%
by our lemma.

00:51:35.910 --> 00:51:39.540 align:middle line:90%
And that's true for every rho.

00:51:39.540 --> 00:51:46.140 align:middle line:84%
And now, since we
have a uniform set,

00:51:46.140 --> 00:51:49.290 align:middle line:84%
and since these rho-covering
numbers are a little bit bigger

00:51:49.290 --> 00:51:56.460 align:middle line:84%
than expected, it tells us that
LxE is a delta, S plus epsilon,

00:51:56.460 --> 00:51:57.185 align:middle line:90%
C set.

00:51:57.185 --> 00:52:02.940 align:middle line:90%


00:52:02.940 --> 00:52:05.970 align:middle line:84%
Actually, here I
needed to put 0 is less

00:52:05.970 --> 00:52:10.810 align:middle line:84%
than S is less than
the minimum of u and 1.

00:52:10.810 --> 00:52:13.760 align:middle line:84%
All of these are hypotheses of
our lemma, so we use them here.

00:52:13.760 --> 00:52:17.360 align:middle line:90%


00:52:17.360 --> 00:52:20.360 align:middle line:84%
Now this is our
starting hypothesis.

00:52:20.360 --> 00:52:21.890 align:middle line:90%
So now we can iterate.

00:52:21.890 --> 00:52:26.560 align:middle line:90%


00:52:26.560 --> 00:52:29.410 align:middle line:84%
So S keeps getting bigger
and bigger, as long

00:52:29.410 --> 00:52:31.820 align:middle line:84%
as it's smaller than
the minimum of u and 1.

00:52:31.820 --> 00:52:34.650 align:middle line:84%
And so it will approach
the minimum of u and 1.

00:52:34.650 --> 00:52:40.180 align:middle line:90%


00:52:40.180 --> 00:52:41.160 align:middle line:90%
And then we're happy.

00:52:41.160 --> 00:52:52.156 align:middle line:90%


00:52:52.156 --> 00:52:54.130 align:middle line:84%
So unlike in the proof
of Beck's theorem,

00:52:54.130 --> 00:52:56.750 align:middle line:84%
we had to use this
lemma many times.

00:52:56.750 --> 00:52:59.030 align:middle line:84%
We used it at many
different scales.

00:52:59.030 --> 00:53:01.520 align:middle line:84%
And also, we had to use
it over and over again.

00:53:01.520 --> 00:53:03.700 align:middle line:84%
And each time we used it,
we improved this exponent

00:53:03.700 --> 00:53:07.690 align:middle line:84%
a little bit until the exponent
approached the exponent

00:53:07.690 --> 00:53:11.620 align:middle line:84%
that we had in the
classical Beck's theorem.

00:53:11.620 --> 00:53:15.370 align:middle line:84%
And so this is sort of
typical of this new paradigm,

00:53:15.370 --> 00:53:17.440 align:middle line:84%
that you can take an
epsilon improvement result

00:53:17.440 --> 00:53:20.290 align:middle line:84%
and use it over and over again
to keep epsilon improving

00:53:20.290 --> 00:53:22.860 align:middle line:84%
something until the thing
reaches the sharp value.

00:53:22.860 --> 00:53:25.810 align:middle line:90%


00:53:25.810 --> 00:53:30.170 align:middle line:84%
Now, you might be wondering
how we started this argument.

00:53:30.170 --> 00:53:33.680 align:middle line:84%
We needed to start with an
S That was bigger than 0.

00:53:33.680 --> 00:53:39.430 align:middle line:84%
And not every set is a
delta, S, C set for any S.

00:53:39.430 --> 00:53:47.260 align:middle line:84%
So to start the argument,
we observe that we had this

00:53:47.260 --> 00:53:51.460 align:middle line:84%
non-concentration in
rectangles condition--

00:53:51.460 --> 00:53:54.760 align:middle line:84%
non-concentration in
rectangles condition here,

00:53:54.760 --> 00:53:58.090 align:middle line:84%
that our set is not too
much in any rectangle.

00:53:58.090 --> 00:53:59.960 align:middle line:84%
We haven't mentioned
that hypothesis yet.

00:53:59.960 --> 00:54:02.170 align:middle line:90%
We use it here to get started.

00:54:02.170 --> 00:54:07.270 align:middle line:84%
So to start with,
non-concentration in rectangles

00:54:07.270 --> 00:54:12.990 align:middle line:84%
easily implies that LxE
is a delta, eta, C set.

00:54:12.990 --> 00:54:18.830 align:middle line:90%


00:54:18.830 --> 00:54:25.550 align:middle line:84%
Because so if E looks like
so, there's not too much of E

00:54:25.550 --> 00:54:27.620 align:middle line:90%
in any rectangle.

00:54:27.620 --> 00:54:28.530 align:middle line:90%
There's our x.

00:54:28.530 --> 00:54:33.650 align:middle line:84%
Therefore, there aren't too
many of these rectangles.

00:54:33.650 --> 00:54:35.690 align:middle line:84%
You can't have-- if
you had a lot of LxE

00:54:35.690 --> 00:54:38.540 align:middle line:84%
in a small angular range, it
would mean, you had a lot of E

00:54:38.540 --> 00:54:39.920 align:middle line:90%
in a small rectangle.

00:54:39.920 --> 00:54:41.410 align:middle line:84%
And that says this
doesn't happen.

00:54:41.410 --> 00:54:45.290 align:middle line:90%


00:54:45.290 --> 00:54:46.820 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

00:54:46.820 --> 00:54:49.070 align:middle line:84%
So now we have
sketched the proof

00:54:49.070 --> 00:54:53.480 align:middle line:84%
of the continuum Beck's
theorem, the first sharp theorem

00:54:53.480 --> 00:54:57.170 align:middle line:84%
in projection theory
distinguishing R from C.

00:54:57.170 --> 00:54:59.837 align:middle line:84%
So let's take a couple
of minutes to digest,

00:54:59.837 --> 00:55:01.420 align:middle line:84%
see if you have
questions or comments.

00:55:01.420 --> 00:55:23.700 align:middle line:90%


00:55:23.700 --> 00:55:24.980 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:55:24.980 --> 00:55:28.680 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: I guess the
second step of the proof

00:55:28.680 --> 00:55:31.680 align:middle line:90%
would be LxE rho.

00:55:31.680 --> 00:55:36.960 align:middle line:84%
Is that the intersection of LxE
with a kind of rho-radius ball?

00:55:36.960 --> 00:55:38.460 align:middle line:90%
LARRY GUTH: Sorry.

00:55:38.460 --> 00:55:48.900 align:middle line:84%
So LxE rho is the rho
neighborhood of LxE.

00:55:48.900 --> 00:55:51.490 align:middle line:84%
Actually, you can
also erase the rho.

00:55:51.490 --> 00:55:54.300 align:middle line:84%
Maybe that's the
best thing to do.

00:55:54.300 --> 00:55:57.330 align:middle line:90%
So LxE is a delta, S, C set.

00:55:57.330 --> 00:55:59.775 align:middle line:84%
And if it's uniform,
it's also a rho, S,

00:55:59.775 --> 00:56:01.385 align:middle line:90%
C set for all the bigger rho's.

00:56:01.385 --> 00:56:03.907 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So rho
greater than delta?

00:56:03.907 --> 00:56:05.490 align:middle line:84%
LARRY GUTH: Yeah,
for all rho greater.

00:56:05.490 --> 00:56:07.390 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:56:07.390 --> 00:56:09.310 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, thank you.

00:56:09.310 --> 00:56:11.710 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

00:56:11.710 --> 00:56:14.180 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:56:14.180 --> 00:56:17.170 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, so recap, so we don't--

00:56:17.170 --> 00:56:20.320 align:middle line:84%
actually, yeah, we don't
need to mention this.

00:56:20.320 --> 00:56:22.040 align:middle line:90%
So say it again.

00:56:22.040 --> 00:56:24.140 align:middle line:90%
So LxE is uniform set.

00:56:24.140 --> 00:56:26.365 align:middle line:84%
If it's delta, S, C,
then it's also rho, S,

00:56:26.365 --> 00:56:28.160 align:middle line:90%
C for all the bigger rho's.

00:56:28.160 --> 00:56:30.790 align:middle line:84%
And so then we get
these covering numbers

00:56:30.790 --> 00:56:33.160 align:middle line:90%
and then get it there.

00:56:33.160 --> 00:56:35.060 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:56:35.060 --> 00:56:36.710 align:middle line:84%
So let me share a
personal reaction.

00:56:36.710 --> 00:56:39.260 align:middle line:84%
So when this paper
came out, first of all,

00:56:39.260 --> 00:56:41.170 align:middle line:84%
I was very impressed
because it was--

00:56:41.170 --> 00:56:43.400 align:middle line:84%
I had been wondering
about this for many years.

00:56:43.400 --> 00:56:46.580 align:middle line:84%
And it's the first sharp
projection-type theorem

00:56:46.580 --> 00:56:49.450 align:middle line:90%
which distinguishes R from C.

00:56:49.450 --> 00:56:55.240 align:middle line:84%
But I also felt kind of unsure
whether this would open the door

00:56:55.240 --> 00:56:57.850 align:middle line:84%
to prove sharp results for
things like the Furstenberg set

00:56:57.850 --> 00:56:59.230 align:middle line:90%
problem.

00:56:59.230 --> 00:57:01.330 align:middle line:84%
Maybe it's a sharp
result, but maybe it's

00:57:01.330 --> 00:57:04.300 align:middle line:84%
about a kind of thing that
somehow is more approachable.

00:57:04.300 --> 00:57:08.290 align:middle line:84%
It was well known classically
that an epsilon improvement

00:57:08.290 --> 00:57:11.920 align:middle line:84%
of something implied a sharp
version of the incidence

00:57:11.920 --> 00:57:13.340 align:middle line:90%
geometry, something here.

00:57:13.340 --> 00:57:15.650 align:middle line:84%
And that's just not the
case for Szemerédi--Trotter.

00:57:15.650 --> 00:57:18.250 align:middle line:84%
Szemerédi--Trotter is not
known to follow from an epsilon

00:57:18.250 --> 00:57:21.910 align:middle line:84%
improvement on some
classical thing.

00:57:21.910 --> 00:57:26.227 align:middle line:84%
And so it wasn't clear to me
if this would open the door

00:57:26.227 --> 00:57:28.060 align:middle line:84%
to prove sharp theorems
about all the things

00:57:28.060 --> 00:57:29.025 align:middle line:90%
we most cared about.

00:57:29.025 --> 00:57:32.500 align:middle line:90%


00:57:32.500 --> 00:57:35.740 align:middle line:84%
So in the rest of this
class, what I want to do

00:57:35.740 --> 00:57:41.950 align:middle line:84%
is to give an outline of the
proof of the Furstenberg set

00:57:41.950 --> 00:57:44.170 align:middle line:84%
conjecture and the
different ingredients that

00:57:44.170 --> 00:57:47.010 align:middle line:84%
go into it, of which this will
turn out to be an important one.

00:57:47.010 --> 00:57:50.530 align:middle line:90%


00:57:50.530 --> 00:57:51.550 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:57:51.550 --> 00:57:55.420 align:middle line:84%
So the first thing to
say is that this proof

00:57:55.420 --> 00:58:03.170 align:middle line:84%
breaks into cases according to
the way the set E is spaced.

00:58:03.170 --> 00:58:06.450 align:middle line:84%
This delta, t, C set, that
definition, on the one hand,

00:58:06.450 --> 00:58:07.650 align:middle line:90%
it's a good definition.

00:58:07.650 --> 00:58:10.190 align:middle line:84%
But under the umbrella
of delta, t, C sets,

00:58:10.190 --> 00:58:12.980 align:middle line:84%
there are several different,
quite different, ways

00:58:12.980 --> 00:58:14.820 align:middle line:90%
that the set E could be spaced.

00:58:14.820 --> 00:58:16.687 align:middle line:84%
And we have to pay
attention to them.

00:58:16.687 --> 00:58:18.520 align:middle line:84%
And we have to treat
them in different ways.

00:58:18.520 --> 00:58:21.600 align:middle line:90%


00:58:21.600 --> 00:58:23.230 align:middle line:90%
So let's explain that.

00:58:23.230 --> 00:58:40.400 align:middle line:90%


00:58:40.400 --> 00:58:49.130 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to split
into cases according

00:58:49.130 --> 00:58:52.623 align:middle line:90%
to how E is spaced.

00:58:52.623 --> 00:58:59.070 align:middle line:90%


00:58:59.070 --> 00:59:03.300 align:middle line:84%
So first of all, let's
assume that E is uniform.

00:59:03.300 --> 00:59:06.550 align:middle line:84%
And now I mentioned the
word "uniform" above,

00:59:06.550 --> 00:59:10.690 align:middle line:84%
but now I'll remember, recall
exactly what is uniform.

00:59:10.690 --> 00:59:12.960 align:middle line:84%
So first of all,
our delta is going

00:59:12.960 --> 00:59:20.580 align:middle line:84%
to be capital delta to the
m, where m is a large number.

00:59:20.580 --> 00:59:25.530 align:middle line:84%
And uniform means that,
for every j going from 1 up

00:59:25.530 --> 00:59:33.120 align:middle line:84%
to m and for every q which
is a delta to the jq, then,

00:59:33.120 --> 00:59:36.160 align:middle line:84%
when I take my set, and
I intersect it with q,

00:59:36.160 --> 00:59:39.570 align:middle line:84%
and I cover it
with cubes or balls

00:59:39.570 --> 00:59:41.910 align:middle line:84%
at the next smaller
scale, delta to the j

00:59:41.910 --> 00:59:46.650 align:middle line:90%
plus 1, that is around Rj.

00:59:46.650 --> 01:00:05.230 align:middle line:90%


01:00:05.230 --> 01:00:07.660 align:middle line:84%
So I'll draw some
pictures in a moment.

01:00:07.660 --> 01:00:12.400 align:middle line:84%
The smallest this Rj could be is
1, and the biggest it could be

01:00:12.400 --> 01:00:15.000 align:middle line:90%
is big delta to the minus 2.

01:00:15.000 --> 01:00:26.800 align:middle line:90%


01:00:26.800 --> 01:00:28.990 align:middle line:84%
Actually, yeah, let me
say a little bit more.

01:00:28.990 --> 01:00:32.170 align:middle line:84%
So the delta
covering number of E

01:00:32.170 --> 01:00:37.890 align:middle line:84%
That's going to be the
product j equals 1 to m of Rj.

01:00:37.890 --> 01:00:41.950 align:middle line:90%


01:00:41.950 --> 01:00:49.360 align:middle line:84%
And another thing we can say is,
if I were to take the product j

01:00:49.360 --> 01:00:52.840 align:middle line:84%
equals 1 to capital
J of Rj, that

01:00:52.840 --> 01:00:57.880 align:middle line:84%
would be the covering number of
E at scale delta to the capital

01:00:57.880 --> 01:00:59.110 align:middle line:90%
J.

01:00:59.110 --> 01:01:02.090 align:middle line:90%
And that should be--

01:01:02.090 --> 01:01:09.970 align:middle line:84%
so let's say-- so
if E is a delta,

01:01:09.970 --> 01:01:16.720 align:middle line:84%
t, C set, then this should
be at least 1 over C

01:01:16.720 --> 01:01:20.860 align:middle line:90%
delta j to the minus t.

01:01:20.860 --> 01:01:23.990 align:middle line:84%
So that gives some information
about these products.

01:01:23.990 --> 01:01:29.890 align:middle line:84%
And being a delta, t, C set is
equivalent to this information

01:01:29.890 --> 01:01:31.130 align:middle line:90%
about these products.

01:01:31.130 --> 01:01:34.732 align:middle line:84%
And so there are many
ways that they could look.

01:01:34.732 --> 01:01:36.940 align:middle line:84%
Let me put up a couple of
examples which also should,

01:01:36.940 --> 01:01:39.530 align:middle line:84%
hopefully, clarify
everything on this board,

01:01:39.530 --> 01:01:41.150 align:middle line:90%
and then we pause for questions.

01:01:41.150 --> 01:02:04.640 align:middle line:90%


01:02:04.640 --> 01:02:09.170 align:middle line:84%
So the first example
that I want to put up

01:02:09.170 --> 01:02:11.900 align:middle line:84%
is that all the
Rj's are the same.

01:02:11.900 --> 01:02:18.980 align:middle line:84%
So Rj is delta to the
minus t for every j.

01:02:18.980 --> 01:02:24.100 align:middle line:84%
And then you'll see
that this will be OK.

01:02:24.100 --> 01:02:28.530 align:middle line:90%


01:02:28.530 --> 01:02:30.730 align:middle line:84%
And I'd like to visualize
this in two ways.

01:02:30.730 --> 01:02:34.730 align:middle line:90%


01:02:34.730 --> 01:02:39.350 align:middle line:84%
So the first way I'd like
to visualize is as a tree.

01:02:39.350 --> 01:02:46.050 align:middle line:84%
So in my visualization,
I picked that delta is 4.

01:02:46.050 --> 01:02:47.333 align:middle line:90%
No, delta is 16.

01:02:47.333 --> 01:02:50.510 align:middle line:90%


01:02:50.510 --> 01:02:57.570 align:middle line:84%
No, sorry, delta is 1/4,
and t is going to be 1.

01:02:57.570 --> 01:03:03.780 align:middle line:84%
So in my visualization, delta
to the minus 1 is going to be 4.

01:03:03.780 --> 01:03:06.030 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to have a tree.

01:03:06.030 --> 01:03:09.220 align:middle line:84%
So that would be R1
guys coming out of it.

01:03:09.220 --> 01:03:11.910 align:middle line:84%
And then each of
these have R2, which

01:03:11.910 --> 01:03:16.320 align:middle line:90%
is also 4, branches coming up.

01:03:16.320 --> 01:03:19.510 align:middle line:84%
I won't draw that, but
they're all the same.

01:03:19.510 --> 01:03:23.650 align:middle line:84%
Now, to the next stage
of our visualization,

01:03:23.650 --> 01:03:26.700 align:middle line:90%
we started with a square.

01:03:26.700 --> 01:03:30.750 align:middle line:84%
And we cut it into smaller
squares of side length delta.

01:03:30.750 --> 01:03:33.720 align:middle line:90%
So that looked like this.

01:03:33.720 --> 01:03:36.210 align:middle line:90%
This is stage 1.

01:03:36.210 --> 01:03:41.941 align:middle line:84%
And R sub 1 is 4, so we took
four, so maybe these four.

01:03:41.941 --> 01:03:45.420 align:middle line:90%


01:03:45.420 --> 01:03:56.800 align:middle line:84%
Stage 2, inside of each
of those four squares,

01:03:56.800 --> 01:04:01.330 align:middle line:84%
I took each of them, and I cut
them into a 4x4 grid of smaller

01:04:01.330 --> 01:04:01.850 align:middle line:90%
squares.

01:04:01.850 --> 01:04:03.470 align:middle line:90%
And I took four of them.

01:04:03.470 --> 01:04:07.390 align:middle line:84%
So I'll do the cutting
carefully here.

01:04:07.390 --> 01:04:10.670 align:middle line:90%
So maybe I took those four.

01:04:10.670 --> 01:04:13.720 align:middle line:90%
And then down here, I took four.

01:04:13.720 --> 01:04:16.900 align:middle line:90%
And over here, I took four.

01:04:16.900 --> 01:04:18.740 align:middle line:90%
And over here, I took four.

01:04:18.740 --> 01:04:21.280 align:middle line:90%


01:04:21.280 --> 01:04:24.520 align:middle line:84%
So our set looks something
like that at stage 2.

01:04:24.520 --> 01:04:27.230 align:middle line:90%
And then you could keep going.

01:04:27.230 --> 01:04:29.450 align:middle line:90%
So this is the first example.

01:04:29.450 --> 01:04:36.250 align:middle line:84%
It's called the AD regular
example, Ahlfors-David regular.

01:04:36.250 --> 01:04:37.750 align:middle line:84%
Ahlfors and David
are two people who

01:04:37.750 --> 01:04:39.710 align:middle line:84%
worked on stuff that
is related to this.

01:04:39.710 --> 01:04:43.360 align:middle line:84%
And the word "regular," I think,
here refers to the fact that all

01:04:43.360 --> 01:04:45.270 align:middle line:84%
the scales are the
same as each other.

01:04:45.270 --> 01:04:49.585 align:middle line:90%


01:04:49.585 --> 01:04:52.095 align:middle line:84%
Now let me show you
an opposite extreme.

01:04:52.095 --> 01:05:17.690 align:middle line:90%


01:05:17.690 --> 01:05:22.060 align:middle line:84%
So this one is called
the well-spaced example.

01:05:22.060 --> 01:05:27.430 align:middle line:84%
So in the well-spaced example
Rj is as big as it could be,

01:05:27.430 --> 01:05:31.990 align:middle line:84%
its maximal value,
for some range of J.

01:05:31.990 --> 01:05:42.190 align:middle line:84%
And then Rj is 1 for
larger J. So as a picture,

01:05:42.190 --> 01:05:43.190 align:middle line:90%
it would look like this.

01:05:43.190 --> 01:05:51.360 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to visualize
with big J as 1, big M is 2,

01:05:51.360 --> 01:05:52.200 align:middle line:90%
like over there.

01:05:52.200 --> 01:05:53.750 align:middle line:90%
So we'll have two stages.

01:05:53.750 --> 01:05:57.783 align:middle line:84%
And so our first stage
is that R1 is 16.

01:05:57.783 --> 01:06:00.320 align:middle line:90%


01:06:00.320 --> 01:06:01.340 align:middle line:90%
I won't draw it up.

01:06:01.340 --> 01:06:04.410 align:middle line:90%
And then R2 is 1.

01:06:04.410 --> 01:06:09.860 align:middle line:84%
So from each point here, we
have just one going down.

01:06:09.860 --> 01:06:13.310 align:middle line:84%
So the tree looks like
this instead of like that,

01:06:13.310 --> 01:06:14.870 align:middle line:84%
a lot of branching
at the beginning

01:06:14.870 --> 01:06:18.820 align:middle line:84%
and then no
branching after that.

01:06:18.820 --> 01:06:21.300 align:middle line:84%
What does it mean our
set looks like in space?

01:06:21.300 --> 01:06:24.950 align:middle line:84%
Well, first, stage
1, I take my square,

01:06:24.950 --> 01:06:27.920 align:middle line:84%
and I break it into 16
squares of side length 1/4.

01:06:27.920 --> 01:06:30.740 align:middle line:90%


01:06:30.740 --> 01:06:34.700 align:middle line:84%
And at stage 1, I
select all 16 of them.

01:06:34.700 --> 01:06:36.270 align:middle line:90%
So the picture looks like this.

01:06:36.270 --> 01:06:40.370 align:middle line:90%


01:06:40.370 --> 01:06:49.290 align:middle line:84%
Now, at stage 2, so I have
cut my square into 16 squares

01:06:49.290 --> 01:06:52.590 align:middle line:84%
of side length 1/4, and I
look inside each one of them.

01:06:52.590 --> 01:06:56.230 align:middle line:84%
I cut that into 16
squares, the smaller size.

01:06:56.230 --> 01:07:02.250 align:middle line:84%
And I pick one of them, and
I do that in all the ones

01:07:02.250 --> 01:07:04.240 align:middle line:84%
I selected at stage 1,
which is all of them.

01:07:04.240 --> 01:07:05.540 align:middle line:90%
So this set looks like this.

01:07:05.540 --> 01:07:16.578 align:middle line:90%


01:07:16.578 --> 01:07:20.280 align:middle line:84%
So this is called
the well-spaced set.

01:07:20.280 --> 01:07:21.630 align:middle line:90%
So I could fix a t.

01:07:21.630 --> 01:07:23.670 align:middle line:84%
I could make a
delta t well-spaced.

01:07:23.670 --> 01:07:25.080 align:middle line:90%
I can fix t and delta.

01:07:25.080 --> 01:07:27.630 align:middle line:84%
I can make a delta
t well-spaced set

01:07:27.630 --> 01:07:31.470 align:middle line:84%
or I can make a delta
Ahlfors regular set.

01:07:31.470 --> 01:07:34.710 align:middle line:84%
And they look rather
different from each other.

01:07:34.710 --> 01:07:36.575 align:middle line:84%
And there's also a
gray area in between.

01:07:36.575 --> 01:07:39.600 align:middle line:90%


01:07:39.600 --> 01:07:47.060 align:middle line:84%
So this one is distinguished
by saying that the points are

01:07:47.060 --> 01:07:48.286 align:middle line:90%
the most separated.

01:07:48.286 --> 01:07:52.520 align:middle line:90%


01:07:52.520 --> 01:07:54.553 align:middle line:84%
So if these points
were like electrons

01:07:54.553 --> 01:07:56.970 align:middle line:84%
that were sitting in this ball,
and they repel each other,

01:07:56.970 --> 01:07:59.190 align:middle line:84%
they would come to a
position that's like this.

01:07:59.190 --> 01:08:02.120 align:middle line:90%
It would be well-spaced.

01:08:02.120 --> 01:08:05.360 align:middle line:84%
And this one is
distinguished by being--

01:08:05.360 --> 01:08:15.295 align:middle line:84%
this is the most clumped which
is allowed for a delta t set.

01:08:15.295 --> 01:08:17.930 align:middle line:90%


01:08:17.930 --> 01:08:20.048 align:middle line:84%
So this isn't the most
clumped possible set.

01:08:20.048 --> 01:08:21.590 align:middle line:84%
I could take these
delta balls, and I

01:08:21.590 --> 01:08:22.890 align:middle line:90%
could smoosh them all there.

01:08:22.890 --> 01:08:24.470 align:middle line:90%
That would be more clumped.

01:08:24.470 --> 01:08:28.140 align:middle line:84%
But if it's a delta t set,
it's not allowed to do that.

01:08:28.140 --> 01:08:30.890 align:middle line:84%
And this is the most
clumped that it could be,

01:08:30.890 --> 01:08:33.630 align:middle line:84%
subject to the definition
of a delta t cell.

01:08:33.630 --> 01:08:36.290 align:middle line:90%


01:08:36.290 --> 01:08:39.215 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

01:08:39.215 --> 01:08:42.319 align:middle line:84%
So there's a range of
spacing conditions.

01:08:42.319 --> 01:08:45.340 align:middle line:84%
And this hopefully gives
a sample of them. yeah?

01:08:45.340 --> 01:08:47.740 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Is there some
sort of energy condition

01:08:47.740 --> 01:08:51.640 align:middle line:84%
or a quantitative measure of
the clumping that would allow

01:08:51.640 --> 01:08:54.729 align:middle line:90%
you to separate the two cases?

01:08:54.729 --> 01:08:57.115 align:middle line:84%
Because they're
both delta, S, C.

01:08:57.115 --> 01:08:57.865 align:middle line:90%
LARRY GUTH: Right.

01:08:57.865 --> 01:09:00.520 align:middle line:84%
So the question, is there
a quantitative measure

01:09:00.520 --> 01:09:03.250 align:middle line:84%
of clumping or concentrating
or spacing that would

01:09:03.250 --> 01:09:05.800 align:middle line:90%
allow us to distinguish them?

01:09:05.800 --> 01:09:08.649 align:middle line:84%
I think the nicest
way to do that is

01:09:08.649 --> 01:09:13.870 align:middle line:84%
this list of Rj's, or perhaps
this list of this list

01:09:13.870 --> 01:09:16.330 align:middle line:90%
of these numbers here.

01:09:16.330 --> 01:09:20.600 align:middle line:84%
So it's not just a single
number, but it is quantitative.

01:09:20.600 --> 01:09:25.029 align:middle line:84%
And if you're willing to have
a list of numbers describing

01:09:25.029 --> 01:09:28.630 align:middle line:84%
your set, then it
does quite a good job.

01:09:28.630 --> 01:09:32.170 align:middle line:84%
It's really a modern
innovation to focus on that.

01:09:32.170 --> 01:09:35.050 align:middle line:84%
In previous times,
people wanted to describe

01:09:35.050 --> 01:09:37.359 align:middle line:84%
the spacing of their set
with one number, which

01:09:37.359 --> 01:09:40.399 align:middle line:84%
would be like the dimension
of the set or the energy

01:09:40.399 --> 01:09:41.810 align:middle line:90%
or something.

01:09:41.810 --> 01:09:45.810 align:middle line:84%
And when they were describing
with just one number,

01:09:45.810 --> 01:09:47.870 align:middle line:84%
then it was lumping
together these two

01:09:47.870 --> 01:09:49.560 align:middle line:90%
rather different behaviors.

01:09:49.560 --> 01:09:54.450 align:middle line:84%
And it turns out to be
important to un-lump

01:09:54.450 --> 01:09:56.950 align:middle line:84%
to prove this theorem, at least
with the proof that we have.

01:09:56.950 --> 01:10:00.200 align:middle line:90%


01:10:00.200 --> 01:10:02.480 align:middle line:90%
OK, good.

01:10:02.480 --> 01:10:07.260 align:middle line:84%
So now I can write down
the outline of the proof.

01:10:07.260 --> 01:10:45.510 align:middle line:90%


01:10:45.510 --> 01:10:48.280 align:middle line:84%
So here is the outline of the
proof of the main theorem,

01:10:48.280 --> 01:10:50.530 align:middle line:84%
or let me say, of the
Furstenberg conjecture.

01:10:50.530 --> 01:10:58.620 align:middle line:90%


01:10:58.620 --> 01:11:00.450 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:11:00.450 --> 01:11:06.630 align:middle line:84%
So first main ingredient is a
theorem of Orponen and Shmerkin

01:11:06.630 --> 01:11:08.220 align:middle line:90%
from '24.

01:11:08.220 --> 01:11:11.100 align:middle line:84%
And they proved that the
Furstenberg conjecture

01:11:11.100 --> 01:11:14.705 align:middle line:90%
holds in the AD regular case.

01:11:14.705 --> 01:11:20.760 align:middle line:90%


01:11:20.760 --> 01:11:26.460 align:middle line:84%
So this is based on and
builds on the stuff--

01:11:26.460 --> 01:11:28.980 align:middle line:84%
builds on the stuff
we talked about today.

01:11:28.980 --> 01:11:34.990 align:middle line:84%
So it builds on the continuum
Beck theorem of OSW,

01:11:34.990 --> 01:11:41.480 align:middle line:84%
which, in turn, built on the
epsilon improvement of OS,

01:11:41.480 --> 01:11:44.970 align:middle line:84%
which, in turn, builds on the
Bourgain projection theorem.

01:11:44.970 --> 01:11:50.480 align:middle line:90%


01:11:50.480 --> 01:11:53.470 align:middle line:84%
It's not at all obvious
given the Beck theorem, just

01:11:53.470 --> 01:11:54.880 align:middle line:90%
an ingredient.

01:11:54.880 --> 01:11:57.880 align:middle line:84%
And so there are also
some great ideas in that

01:11:57.880 --> 01:11:59.720 align:middle line:90%
we'll talk about next time.

01:11:59.720 --> 01:12:04.360 align:middle line:84%
But also, it involves
some special structure

01:12:04.360 --> 01:12:06.135 align:middle line:90%
of the AD regular case.

01:12:06.135 --> 01:12:14.830 align:middle line:90%


01:12:14.830 --> 01:12:19.340 align:middle line:84%
We'll talk about that
a lot on Thursday.

01:12:19.340 --> 01:12:23.900 align:middle line:84%
The second ingredient is a
theorem of Guth, Solomon, Wang.

01:12:23.900 --> 01:12:25.690 align:middle line:90%
So I was involved a little bit.

01:12:25.690 --> 01:12:27.140 align:middle line:84%
It's is a slightly
older theorem.

01:12:27.140 --> 01:12:29.200 align:middle line:90%
It's from 2019.

01:12:29.200 --> 01:12:31.750 align:middle line:84%
And we proved that the
Furstenberg conjecture

01:12:31.750 --> 01:12:34.455 align:middle line:90%
holds in the well-spaced case.

01:12:34.455 --> 01:12:39.250 align:middle line:90%


01:12:39.250 --> 01:12:42.000 align:middle line:84%
And it's based on
the Fourier method.

01:12:42.000 --> 01:12:48.010 align:middle line:90%


01:12:48.010 --> 01:12:50.060 align:middle line:84%
This is much less
difficult than this.

01:12:50.060 --> 01:12:52.660 align:middle line:84%
It's the Fourier method
that we explored for a while

01:12:52.660 --> 01:12:55.220 align:middle line:84%
with a little bit of
extra something something.

01:12:55.220 --> 01:12:57.880 align:middle line:84%
How do you take advantage
of being really well spaced

01:12:57.880 --> 01:13:01.840 align:middle line:90%
instead of just AD regular?

01:13:01.840 --> 01:13:04.330 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:13:04.330 --> 01:13:06.290 align:middle line:90%
Good.

01:13:06.290 --> 01:13:15.490 align:middle line:84%
So now, when I presented
these two possibilities,

01:13:15.490 --> 01:13:17.860 align:middle line:84%
the way I had
thought about them is

01:13:17.860 --> 01:13:22.510 align:middle line:84%
that these are just two opposite
ends of a whole gray spectrum.

01:13:22.510 --> 01:13:25.240 align:middle line:84%
And so if you have a method
that works in one end,

01:13:25.240 --> 01:13:29.080 align:middle line:84%
and you have a method that
works on the other end,

01:13:29.080 --> 01:13:31.760 align:middle line:84%
I guess you might hope to
have a general thing that

01:13:31.760 --> 01:13:34.350 align:middle line:84%
sort of combines them both
and works for everything.

01:13:34.350 --> 01:13:37.255 align:middle line:84%
But there's still all
this stuff in the middle.

01:13:37.255 --> 01:13:40.220 align:middle line:90%


01:13:40.220 --> 01:13:43.220 align:middle line:84%
And it turns out-- and I think
this is surprisingly important

01:13:43.220 --> 01:13:44.340 align:middle line:90%
in its own right--

01:13:44.340 --> 01:13:46.730 align:middle line:84%
that the proof of the
theorem actually reduces

01:13:46.730 --> 01:13:50.420 align:middle line:90%
to just those two cases.

01:13:50.420 --> 01:14:00.140 align:middle line:84%
So the third ingredient
is a multi-scale argument

01:14:00.140 --> 01:14:04.250 align:middle line:84%
which shows that the
Furstenberg conjecture actually

01:14:04.250 --> 01:14:10.400 align:middle line:84%
reduces to the AD regular
case and what they

01:14:10.400 --> 01:14:14.510 align:middle line:90%
call the semi well-spaced case.

01:14:14.510 --> 01:14:17.210 align:middle line:84%
So this is a small
generalization

01:14:17.210 --> 01:14:19.040 align:middle line:84%
of this case that
can be handled by,

01:14:19.040 --> 01:14:24.350 align:middle line:84%
more or less, the same methods
using Fourier analysis.

01:14:24.350 --> 01:14:28.015 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

01:14:28.015 --> 01:14:31.840 align:middle line:90%


01:14:31.840 --> 01:14:34.320 align:middle line:84%
So in each of
these, I think there

01:14:34.320 --> 01:14:39.210 align:middle line:84%
is something worth talking
about and worth remembering,

01:14:39.210 --> 01:14:41.702 align:middle line:84%
an idea that could
be useful certainly

01:14:41.702 --> 01:14:43.410 align:middle line:84%
in other problems in
this field and maybe

01:14:43.410 --> 01:14:45.120 align:middle line:90%
in other parts of math.

01:14:45.120 --> 01:14:50.160 align:middle line:84%
We have two more classes,
so I'll [INAUDIBLE].

01:14:50.160 --> 01:14:53.010 align:middle line:84%
My goal is, in the two classes,
to say something substantial

01:14:53.010 --> 01:14:56.610 align:middle line:84%
about each of these three ideas
which fit together to prove

01:14:56.610 --> 01:14:58.030 align:middle line:90%
the Furstenberg conjecture.

01:14:58.030 --> 01:15:04.410 align:middle line:90%


01:15:04.410 --> 01:15:05.470 align:middle line:90%
OK, good.

01:15:05.470 --> 01:15:08.990 align:middle line:90%
Any last questions or comments?

01:15:08.990 --> 01:15:11.745 align:middle line:90%


01:15:11.745 --> 01:15:13.170 align:middle line:90%
Mm-hmm?

01:15:13.170 --> 01:15:15.730 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Within each of
these individual cases,

01:15:15.730 --> 01:15:20.472 align:middle line:84%
how much variation is there
in the structure of the sets?

01:15:20.472 --> 01:15:21.930 align:middle line:84%
Because it's not
really [INAUDIBLE]

01:15:21.930 --> 01:15:26.950 align:middle line:84%
kind of rearranging [INAUDIBLE]
points within one of the boxes

01:15:26.950 --> 01:15:29.770 align:middle line:90%
does a lot or does a little.

01:15:29.770 --> 01:15:30.760 align:middle line:90%
LARRY GUTH: Yeah.

01:15:30.760 --> 01:15:33.070 align:middle line:90%
OK, so the question is--

01:15:33.070 --> 01:15:35.420 align:middle line:84%
so we've taken all
the delta, t sets.

01:15:35.420 --> 01:15:37.270 align:middle line:84%
We have then divided
them according

01:15:37.270 --> 01:15:38.840 align:middle line:90%
to their branching function.

01:15:38.840 --> 01:15:41.500 align:middle line:84%
And one extreme is the AD
regular and one extreme

01:15:41.500 --> 01:15:43.000 align:middle line:90%
is the well-spaced.

01:15:43.000 --> 01:15:46.240 align:middle line:84%
And then the question is, if
you look among different sets

01:15:46.240 --> 01:15:47.720 align:middle line:84%
with the same
branching function,

01:15:47.720 --> 01:15:50.380 align:middle line:84%
like among different
AD regular sets,

01:15:50.380 --> 01:15:52.245 align:middle line:84%
how different are
they from each other?

01:15:52.245 --> 01:15:55.180 align:middle line:90%


01:15:55.180 --> 01:16:06.250 align:middle line:84%
Well, I will try to answer
that by drawing a second AD

01:16:06.250 --> 01:16:09.490 align:middle line:84%
regular set in blue that we can
compare to the one in white.

01:16:09.490 --> 01:16:13.600 align:middle line:84%
So I should pick four big
squares, and in each of them,

01:16:13.600 --> 01:16:15.705 align:middle line:90%
I'll draw four dots.

01:16:15.705 --> 01:16:29.770 align:middle line:90%


01:16:29.770 --> 01:16:35.890 align:middle line:84%
I would say that the sort of
spacing feel of these dots

01:16:35.890 --> 01:16:40.120 align:middle line:84%
is the same in all the
examples that are AD regular.

01:16:40.120 --> 01:16:43.105 align:middle line:84%
On the other hand, actually,
let me draw another example.

01:16:43.105 --> 01:16:44.730 align:middle line:84%
This would be-- here's
another example.

01:16:44.730 --> 01:16:55.570 align:middle line:90%


01:16:55.570 --> 01:17:03.490 align:middle line:84%
So something else is a little
different about this example.

01:17:03.490 --> 01:17:07.750 align:middle line:84%
And so yeah, so there are
some more delicate things that

01:17:07.750 --> 01:17:09.580 align:middle line:84%
could be different
about the different AD

01:17:09.580 --> 01:17:12.310 align:middle line:90%
regular examples, even though--

01:17:12.310 --> 01:17:14.770 align:middle line:84%
so what's the same about
them is you give me a radius,

01:17:14.770 --> 01:17:15.680 align:middle line:90%
your favorite radius.

01:17:15.680 --> 01:17:17.980 align:middle line:84%
You stick down a ball
of that radius and count

01:17:17.980 --> 01:17:19.340 align:middle line:90%
how many points are in there.

01:17:19.340 --> 01:17:22.635 align:middle line:84%
That will be the same
for any AD regular set.

01:17:22.635 --> 01:17:29.120 align:middle line:90%


01:17:29.120 --> 01:17:30.480 align:middle line:90%
But there are delicate things.

01:17:30.480 --> 01:17:32.480 align:middle line:84%
Actually, another very
important, delicate thing

01:17:32.480 --> 01:17:34.910 align:middle line:84%
that would be different
is-- so let's now think

01:17:34.910 --> 01:17:36.140 align:middle line:90%
about the well-spaced set.

01:17:36.140 --> 01:17:40.670 align:middle line:84%
An example of a well-spaced
set is an integer grid.

01:17:40.670 --> 01:17:42.540 align:middle line:84%
That has some
special properties.

01:17:42.540 --> 01:17:45.920 align:middle line:84%
It has translation symmetry
and stuff like that.

01:17:45.920 --> 01:17:48.020 align:middle line:84%
A typical well-spaced
set will still

01:17:48.020 --> 01:17:49.890 align:middle line:84%
have one point in
each of these boxes,

01:17:49.890 --> 01:17:51.990 align:middle line:84%
but it won't have
additive structure.

01:17:51.990 --> 01:17:53.580 align:middle line:84%
It won't have
translation symmetry.

01:17:53.580 --> 01:17:57.560 align:middle line:84%
It won't have-- and it
won't have very many lines

01:17:57.560 --> 01:17:59.270 align:middle line:90%
that go through many points.

01:17:59.270 --> 01:18:01.640 align:middle line:84%
So those kinds of
things are different

01:18:01.640 --> 01:18:04.560 align:middle line:84%
among the different sets with
the same spacing condition.

01:18:04.560 --> 01:18:08.480 align:middle line:90%


01:18:08.480 --> 01:18:10.530 align:middle line:84%
OK, well, let's stop
there for today.

01:18:10.530 --> 01:18:14.950 align:middle line:84%
And we'll talk more about these
things on our last two classes.

01:18:14.950 --> 01:18:22.000 align:middle line:90%